{"title_page": "2014 Toronto municipal election", "text_new": "{{For|information about the election for mayor|Toronto mayoral election, 2014}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name     = 2014 Toronto municipal election\n| country           = Toronto\n| type              = Municipal\n| ongoing           = no\n| previous_election = 2010 Toronto municipal election\n| previous_year     = 2010\n| next_election     = 2018 Toronto municipal election\n| next_year         = 2018\n| election_date     = October 27, 2014\n| image1            = \n| color1            = \n| candidate1        = \n| popular_vote1     = \n| percentage1       = \n| image2            = \n| color2            = \n| candidate2        = \n| popular_vote2     = \n| percentage2       = \n| image3            = \n| candidate3        = \n| color3            = \n| popular_vote3     = \n| percentage3       = \n| map_image         = Torontowards.PNG\n| map_size          = 350px\n| map_caption       = The ward boundaries for the 2014 election. The Mayor and French school board trustees are elected across the city, councillors in their respective wards, and English public and Catholic trustees on a ward or dual-ward basis.\n| title             = Council\n| before_election   = {{small|([[2014 Toronto municipal election#Incumbents 2010-2014|see table]])}}\n| before_party      = \n| after_election    = {{small|[[Toronto City Council 2014\u20132018]]}}\n| after_party       = \n}}\nThe '''2014 Toronto municipal election''' was held on October 27, 2014 to elect a [[Mayor of Toronto|mayor]] and 44 [[Toronto City Council|city councillors]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. In addition, school trustees were elected to the [[Toronto District School Board]], [[Toronto Catholic District School Board]], [[Conseil scolaire de district du Centre-Sud-Ouest]] and [[Conseil scolaire de district catholique Centre-Sud]]. The election was held [[2014 Ontario municipal elections|in conjunction with those held in other municipalities]] in the province of [[Ontario]]. Candidate registration opened on January 2, 2014 and closed on September 12, 2014 at 2pm EST.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www1.toronto.ca/wps/portal/contentonly?vgnextoid=a506fc9b6462c310VgnVCM10000068d60f89RCRD|title=Complete List of Key Dates - Candidates - Elections {{!}} City of Toronto|language=en-CA|access-date=2016-09-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911113732/http://www1.toronto.ca/wps/portal/contentonly?vgnextoid=a506fc9b6462c310VgnVCM10000068d60f89RCRD|archive-date=2014-09-11|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==City council==\nCity councillors were elected to represent Toronto's 44 wards at [[Toronto City Council]]. 36 out of 37 incumbent councillors were re-elected to their previous seat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.torontoelectionstudy.com/blog/|title=Findings|website=Toronto Election Study|language=en-CA|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n\n===Incumbents 2010-2014===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Ward\n!Councillor\n!Other roles\n|-\n|1 Etobicoke North\n|Vincent Crisanti\n|Chair of Etobicoke and York Community Council\n|-\n|2 Etobicoke North\n|Doug Ford \n|Vice-chair of Budget Committee\n|- \n|3 Etobicoke Centre\n|Peter Leon\n|\n|-\n|4 Etobicoke Centre\n|Gloria Lindsay Luby\n|Acting Chair of Toronto Police Services Board (June\u2013November, 2013)\n|-\n|5 Etobicoke-Lakeshore\n|James Maloney\n|\n|-\n|6 Etobicoke-Lakeshore\n|Mark Grimes\n|\n|-\n|7 York West\n|Giorgio Mammoliti\n|Chair of Community Development and Recreation\n|-\n|8 York West\n|Anthony Perruzza\n|\n|-\n|9 York Centre\n|Maria Augimeri \n|Chair of Toronto Transit Commission and North York Community Council\n|-\n|10 York Centre\n|James Pasternak\n|\n|-\n|11 York South-Weston\n|Frances Nunziata\n|Toronto City Council Speaker\n|-\n|12 York South-Weston\n|Frank Di Giorgio\n|Budget Chief\n|-\n|13 Parkdale-High Park\n|Sarah Doucette\n|Vice-chair of Toronto Board of Health\n|-\n|14 Parkdale-High Park\n|Gord Perks\n|Chair of Central Toronto and East York Community Council\n|-\n|15 Eglinton-Lawrence\n|Josh Colle\n|\n|-\n|16 Eglinton-Lawrence\n|Karen Stintz\n|Former Chair, TTC\n|-\n|17 Davenport \n|Cesar Palacio\n|Chair of Licensing and Standards Committee\n|-\n|18 Davenport\n|Ana Bail\u00e3o \n|\n|-\n|19 Trinity-Spadina\n|Mike Layton\n|\n|-\n|20 Trinity-Spadina\n|Ceta Ramkhalawansingh\n|\n|-\n|21 St. Paul's\n|Joe Mihevc\n|Vice-chair of Toronto Board of Health\n|-\n|22 St. Paul's\n|Josh Matlow\n|\n|-\n|23 Willowdale\n|John Filion\n|Chair of Toronto Board of Health\n|-\n|24 Willowdale\n|David Shiner\n|\n|-\n|25 Don Valley West\n|Jaye Robinson\n|\n|-\n|26 Don Valley West\n|John Parker\n|Deputy Speaker of Toronto City Council\n|-\n|27 Toronto Centre-Rosedale\n|Kristyn Wong-Tam\n|\n|-\n|28 Toronto Centre-Rosedale\n|Pam McConnell\n|\n|-\n|29 Toronto-Danforth\n|Mary Fragedakis\n|\n|-\n|30 Toronto-Danforth\n|Paula Fletcher \n|\n|-\n|31 Beaches-East York\n|Janet Davis\n|\n|-\n|32 Beaches-East York\n|Mary-Margaret McMahon\n|\n|-\n|33 Don Valley East\n|Shelley Carroll\n|\n|-\n|34 Don Valley East\n|Denzil Minnan-Wong \n|Chair of the Board of Public Works\n|-\n|35 Scarborough Southwest\n|Michelle Berardinetti\n|Chair of Scarborough Community Council\n|-\n|36 Scarborough Southwest\n|Gary Crawford\n|\n|-\n|37 Scarborough Centre\n|Michael Thompson\n|\n|-\n|38 Scarborough Centre\n|Glenn De Baeremaeker\n|\n|-\n|39 Scarborough Agincourt\n|Mike Del Grande\n|\n|-\n|40 Scarborough Agincourt\n|Norm Kelly\n|Deputy Mayor, Chair of Parks and Environment Committee.\n|-\n|41 Scarborough-Rouge River\n|Chin Lee\n|Vice-chair of Toronto Police Services Board, Chair of Toronto Zoo.\n|-\n|42 Scarborough-Rouge River\n|Raymond Cho\n|\n|-\n|43 Scarborough East\n|Paul Ainslie\n|Chair of Toronto Library Board, Vice-chair of Toronto Zoo\n|-\n|44 Scarborough East\n|Ron Moeser \n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==School boards==\nSchool trustees were elected to the: \n* [[Toronto District School Board]]\n* [[Toronto Catholic District School Board]]\n* [[Conseil scolaire de district du Centre-Sud-Ouest]]\n* [[Conseil scolaire de district catholique Centre-Sud]].{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n==Issues==\n\n===Transit===\nIn the [[Greater Toronto Area]], the average time spent commuting to and from work is 80 minutes, making it the worst among 19 large urban areas in [[North America]].<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/yourtoronto/yourcitymycity/2010/03/30/toronto_commuting_times_worst_of_19_major_cities_study_says.html Toronto commuting times worst of 19 major cities, study says]</ref> Transit was a major issue because of several controversial projects in the city, such as the use of [[rapid transit|subway]] versus [[light rail transit]] technology to replace the [[Scarborough RT]], congested [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]] [[streetcar]]s, construction disruption from the [[Eglinton Crosstown]], and the electrification of the [[Union Pearson Express]]. Proposals by [[Metrolinx]] to impose revenue tools to fund transit were also a source of controversy.<ref name=\"Globe Column Transit\">[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/whats-on-the-minds-of-toronto-voters-transit/article16395573/ What\u2019s on the minds of Toronto voters? Transit]</ref> The [[Toronto Board of Trade|Toronto Region Board of Trade]] and TTC CEO Andy Byford stated that transit must be a critical issue that voters consider in the election.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/toronto-board-of-trade-president-urges-mayoral-candidates-to-focus-on-issues/article16229022/ Toronto \u2018tired of the frustrations\u2019 at city hall, board of trade president says]</ref><ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2014/01/09/visionaries_needed_at_city_hall_ttcs_andy_byford_says.html TTC\u2019s Andy Byford says transit visionaries are needed at city hall]</ref>\n\n===Rob Ford===\nMuch attention was given to [[Timeline of Rob Ford video scandal|allegations against Rob Ford]] during the 2014 election, and his admission on November 5, 2013, to smoking [[crack cocaine]].<ref>[http://metronews.ca/voices/urban-compass-toronto-2/922169/toronto-election-to-be-a-referendum-on-rob-ford/ Toronto election to be a referendum on Rob Ford] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140130135407/http://metronews.ca/voices/urban-compass-toronto-2/922169/toronto-election-to-be-a-referendum-on-rob-ford/ |date=2014-01-30 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thegridto.com/city/politics/your-2014-election-survival-guide/ |title=Your 2014 election survival guide |access-date=2014-01-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110121937/http://www.thegridto.com/city/politics/your-2014-election-survival-guide/ |archive-date=2014-01-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Star crack admission\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2013/11/05/rob_ford_yes_i_have_smoked_crack_cocaine.html |title=Rob Ford : 'Yes, I have smoked crack cocaine.' &#124; Toronto Star |publisher=Toronto Star |date= |accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Ranked ballots and voting rights for permanent residents===\nOn June 11, 2013, Toronto City Council passed a motion asking the [[Government of Ontario]] to give [[permanent residents]] the right to participate in municipal elections and to allow the city to adopt [[Instant-runoff voting|ranked choice balloting]], which would give voters the option to rank candidates in order of preference. Twenty-six councillors supported the motion and fifteen were against it.<ref>http://app.toronto.ca/tmmis/viewAgendaItemHistory.do?item=2013.GM22.15</ref><ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2013/06/11/toronto_city_council_backs_radical_change_to_ranked_ballots_and_letting_noncitizens_participate.html Toronto city council backs radical change to ranked ballots and letting non-citizens participate]</ref><ref>[http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/06/11/councillors-vote-to-seek-end-of-first-past-the-post-system-in-city-elections/ Councillors vote to seek end of \u2018first past the post\u2019 system in city elections]</ref> Following the council move, the [[Ranked Ballot Initiative of Toronto]] sent a petition with over eight thousand signatures to the provincial government, endorsing the council motion and requesting swift action on electoral reform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unlockdemocracy.ca/mah_event|title=Municipal Ranked Ballots: Major Announcement on Monday!|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref> The [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal]] MPP for Scarborough-Guildwood, [[Mitzie Hunter]], then introduced the Toronto Ranked Ballots Election Act in March 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontla.on.ca/web/bills/bills_detail.do?locale=en&BillID=2948&isCurrent=false&detailPage=bills_detail_the_bill|title=Legislative Assembly of Ontario {{!}} Bills & Lawmaking {{!}} Past & Present {{!}} 40:2 Bill 166, Toronto Ranked Ballot Elections Act, 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ontla.on.ca|publisher=|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref> The bill was passed on the second reading but died prematurely when the [[2014 Ontario general election|Ontario election]] was called.\n\n===Other===\nIn the wake of substance abuse allegations against Rob Ford, the possibility of reversing the [[Amalgamation of Toronto#1998 amalgamation|1998 amalgamation of Toronto]] was raised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/commentary/2013/05/29/how_the_rob_ford_crack_scandal_could_save_toronto.html|title=How the Rob Ford crack scandal could save Toronto {{!}} Toronto Star|website=thestar.com|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thetyee.ca/Opinion/2013/11/11/Rob-Ford-De-Amalgamate/|title=While the Crack Pipe's Hot, De-Amalgamate Toronto {{!}} The Tyee|last=Anderson|first=Mitchell|date=2013-11-11|language=English|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n===Ward 1 - Etobicoke North===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 150px;\" | Candidate Name\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 100px;\" | Number of votes\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 100px;\" | % of votes\n!