eferences==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.toronto.ca/elections/index.htm City of Toronto election webpage]\n\n{{Toronto elections}}\n\n[[Category:Municipal elections in Toronto|2014]]\n[[Category:2014 Ontario municipal elections]]\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "tidy wikitable options", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014_Toronto_municipal_election"}
{"title_page": "Gila Martow", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Gila Martow\n| image         = File:Gila Martow.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|MPP]]\n| office1       = Parliamentary Assistant to the Minister of Francophone Affairs\n| term_start1   = November 29, 2018\n| term_end1     = \n| minister1     = [[Caroline Mulroney]]\n| parliament2   = Ontario Provincial\n| term_start2   = February 13, 2014\n| term_end2     = \n| predecessor2  = [[Peter Shurman]]\n| successor2    =\n| riding2 = [[Thornhill (provincial electoral district)|Thornhill]]\n| party         = [[Ontario Progressive Conservative Party|Progressive Conservative]]\n| birth_name  = Gila Deborah Gladstone\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1961|06|05}}\n| birth_place   = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]\n| residence     = [[Thornhill, Ontario]]\n| spouse       = \n| alma_mater    = [[University of Waterloo School of Optometry and Vision Science]]\n| occupation    = Optometrist\n}}\n'''Gila Deborah Martow''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Gladstone'''; born June 5, 1961) is a politician in [[Ontario]], Canada. She represents the electoral district of [[Thornhill (provincial electoral district)|Thornhill]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] as a member of the [[Ontario Progressive Conservative Party]].<ref name=global /> She held the position of [[Parliamentary Assistant]] to the Minister of Labour until November 2018, when she was appointed Parliamentary Assistant to [[Ministry of Francophone Affairs|Francophone Affairs Minister]] [[Caroline Mulroney]] following the departure of [[Amanda Simard]] from the PC Caucus.\n\n==Background==\nOriginally from [[Chomedey, Quebec]], Martow was an [[optometrist]]. She and her husband, an ophthalmologist, jointly ran an eye clinic at the [[Markham Stouffville Hospital]].<ref name=yorkregion>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/4314953-parties-get-set-as-thornhill-byelection-called/ |title=Parties get set as Thornhill byelection called |date=January 14, 2014 |first=Simone |last=Joseph |newspaper=yorkregion.com |publisher=Metroland Media}}.</ref>\n\nMartow's maternal grandparents lived on a [[kibbutz]] organized by the [[Hashomer Hatzair]] [[Marxist]]-[[Zionist]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hashomer |first1=Hatzair |title=Hashomer Hatzair records, 1938-1942|url=https://magnes.berkeley.edu/collections/archives/western-jewish-americana/hashomer-hatzair-records-1938-1942 |website=The Magnes Collection of Jewish Art and Life |publisher=The Regents of the University of California. |accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref> youth movement in the early 1930s in [[Mandatory Palestine]] (later to become [[Israel]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontla.on.ca/web/house-proceedings/house_detail.do?locale=fr&Date=2015-04-23 |publisher=Legislative Assembly of Ontario |date=April 23, 2015 |title=House proceedings (hansard)}}</ref> Martow attended the socialist movement's summer camp, [[Camp Shomria]], from 1973 to 1977. The camp's Mia Gladstone Art Program is named in memory of Martow's mother.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cjnews.com/news/hashomer-hatzair-marks-85-years-canada|title=Hashomer Hatzair marks 85 years in Canada|date=August 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Political activism==\nIn 2007, she was a spokesperson for the Multi-Faith Coalition. During the [[2007 Ontario general election|provincial election that year]], she supported Progressive Conservative leader [[John Tory]]'s plan to create funding among Ontario\u2019s private faith-based schools. She said, \"By not funding non-Catholic faith-based schools, there is going to be social unrest. This is discrimination against non-Catholics.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Eby|first=Chris|title=Ont. Tories trash Liberal promise-keeping record|url=http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ont-tories-trash-liberal-promise-keeping-record-1.255708|work=CTV Toronto News|publisher=CTV|accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>\nMartow's first run for elected office was in 2010, when she ran for city council in Vaughan Ward 5, placing second.\n\n==Ontario legislature==\nIn early 2014, she ran in a [[by-election]] in the riding of [[Thornhill (provincial electoral district)|Thornhill]] to replace the retiring [[Peter Shurman]]. She defeated [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal]] candidate Sandra Yeung Racco on February 13, 2014.<ref name=global>{{cite news |url=http://globalnews.ca/news/1149407/tories-hold-thornhill-ndp-leading-in-niagara-falls-in-ontario-byelections |title=NDP win Niagara Falls, Tories hold Thornhill in Ontario byelections |publisher=Global News |date=February 13, 2014}}</ref> Four months later she ran again in the [[2014 Ontario general election|2014 provincial election]]. She faced Racco again in a rematch. Initially Racco was declared the winner but the decision was reversed the next day following the official [[Elections Ontario]] tally of the vote. Martow was declared the winner by 85 votes.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's official: PC Martow wins Thornhill in wake of vote tally error |url=http://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/4579262-pc-martow-declared-winner-in-thornhill-in-wake-of-vote-tallying-error/ |publisher=York Region |accessdate=June 14, 2014 |date=June 14, 2014}}</ref> A recount was done and Martow was declared the winner on June 23, 2014 by a margin of 106 votes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Martow proclaimed winner in recount |url=http://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/4594049-candidates-not-present-for-today-s-thornhill-vote-recount/ |date=June 23, 2014 |newspaper=York Region |publisher=Metroland Media}}</ref>\n\nOn December 1, 2016, Martow presented a motion in the legislature rejecting the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions]] campaign against Israel. It passed by a vote of 49-5 with the governing Liberals and PCs supporting, and NDP opposing.\n\nIn the past, Martow has served as the PC Critic for Intergovernmental Affairs (2014) and as the Anti-Racism Secretariat (2016).  She then served in the [[shadow cabinet]] as the critic for:  Children, Youth, and Families;  GTA Issues;  and Francophone Affairs until 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontla.on.ca/web/members/members_detail.do?locale=en&ID=7245|title=Legislative Assembly of Ontario {{!}} Members (MPPs) {{!}} Current MPPs {{!}} Gila Martow, MPP (Thornhill)|website=www.ontla.on.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-02-10}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Progressive Conservatives formed government following the [[2018 Ontario general election|2018 provincial election]], Martow was appointed Parliamentary Assistant to [[Ministry of Labour (Ontario)|Labour Minister]] [[Laurie Scott (politician)|Laurie Scott]] by Premier [[Doug Ford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2018/06/premier-ford-announces-parliamentary-assistant-assignments-as-part-of-ontarios-government-for-the-pe.html|title=Premier Ford Announces Parliamentary Assistant Assignments as Part of Ontario's Government for the People|website=news.ontario.ca}}</ref> On November 29, 2018, Premier Ford announced that Martow would become the Parliamentary Assistant to the Minister of Francophone Affairs, [[Caroline Mulroney]] and that [[Jane McKenna]] would take over her position as the Parliamentary Assistant to the Minister of Labour.\n\n==Election results==\n===Provincial===\n{{CANelec/top|ON|2018|Thornhill (provincial electoral district)|Thornhill|percent=yes|change=yes|}}\n{{CANelec|ON|PC|Gila Martow|28,889|61.13|+17.18}}\n{{CANelec|ON|NDP|Ezra Tanen|9,134|19.33|+11.17}}\n{{CANelec|ON|Liberal|Sabi Ahsan|6,985|14.78|-29.00}}\n{{CANelec|ON|Green|Rachel Dokhoian|1,043|2.21|-0.27}}\n{{CANelec|ON|Libertarian|Mike Holmes|621|1.31|+0.15}}\n{{CANelec|ON|NOTA|Above Znoneofthe|410|0.87|}}\n{{CANelec|ON|Moderate|Aleksei Polyakov|177|0.37|}}\n{{CANelec/total|Total valid votes|47,261|100.0 &nbsp;}}\n{{CANelec/hold|ON|PC|+13.24}}<!--\n{{CANelec/total|Total rejected, unmarked and declined ballots|||}}\n{{CANelec/total|Turnout|56.85||}}\n{{CANelec/total|Eligible voters