{"title_page": "Kinga Surma", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name          = Kinga Surma\n| image         = Kinga Surma Apr2018.jpg\n| caption       =\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|MPP]]\n| office1       = Associate Minister of Transportation (GTA)\n| premier1      = [[Doug Ford]]\n| term_start1   = June 20, 2019\n| term_end1     = \n| predecessor1  = ''Position established''\n| successor1    = [[Incumbent]]\n\n| parliament2   = Ontario Provincial\n| term_start2   = June 7, 2018\n| term_end      =\n| predecessor2  = [[Yvan Baker]] \n| successor2    =\n| riding2       = [[Etobicoke Centre (provincial electoral district)|Etobicoke Centre]]\n| party         = [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Progressive Conservative]]\n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = Poland<ref>https://www.kingasurma.com/about</ref>\n| nationality   = Canadian \n| residence     = [[Etobicoke]], [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n| occupation    = \n| spouse        = \n| children      = \n| alma_mater    = [[University of Guelph]]<br />[[Ryerson University]]\n}}\n\n'''Kinga Surma''' (born ca. 1987/1988 in [[Poland]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=InLFRG5b8aw&t=373s \"Kinga Surma Christmas PCParty\"\nYouTube video uploaded by GoniecTV Toronto, Surma reveals she was born in Poland, moved to Canada when she was 4, which was 25 years from  Feb. 2017</ref>) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician, who was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] in the [[2018 Ontario general election|2018 provincial election]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/queenspark/2018/06/07/pcs-kinga-surma-takes-lead-in-etobicoke-centre.html| title=Kinga Surma wins Etobicoke Centre for PCs| first=Tamara| last=Shephard| date=June 7, 2018|  newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> She represents the riding of [[Etobicoke Centre (provincial electoral district)|Etobicoke Centre]] as a member of the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario]].\n\nSurma ran for City Councillor in Ward 5 in the [[2014 Toronto municipal election|2014 Toronto Municipal election]] and placed second with 13.9% of the vote.<ref name=\"to2014\" />\n\n==Election results==\n{{Ontario provincial election, 2018/Etobicoke Centre}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''2014 Toronto election, Ward 5'''<ref name=\"to2014\">{{cite web|url=https://www.toronto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/9021-election-2014-councillor-poll-by-poll-results.pdf|title=City of Toronto Official Results}}</ref> \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|Justin Di Ciano ||align=right|15,362 ||align=right|54.2 \n|-\n|Kinga Surma ||align=right|3,936 ||align=right|13.9\n|-\n|Guy Bowie ||align=right|2,744 ||align=right|9.7 \n|-\n|Walter Melnyk ||align=right|1,399 ||align=right|4.9 \n|-\n|Raymond Desilets ||align=right|1,365 ||align=right|4.8 \n|-\n|Tony D'aversa ||align=right|1,307 ||align=right|4.6 \n|-\n|Nikola Samac ||align=right|1,019 ||align=right|3.6 \n|-\n|Magda Chelminska ||align=right|645 ||align=right|2.3 \n|-\n|George Lehto ||align=right|565 ||align=right|1.9 \n|-\n!Total||align=right|28,342 ||align=right|100 \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ontario MPPs}}\n{{Ford Ministry}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Surma, Kinga}}\n[[Category:Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario MPPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of Ontario]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Etobicoke]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Canada]]\n[[Category:Women MPPs in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{Ontario-MPP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name         