{"title_page": "Raymond Cho (politician)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Raymond Cho|Raymond Cho (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name         = Raymond Cho\n| native_name      = \uc870\uc131\uc900\n| native_name_lang = kr\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|MPP]]\n| image        = Raymond Cho.png\n| caption      =\n\n| office        = [[Ministry of Seniors Affairs|Ontario Minister of Seniors and Accessibility]] \n| premier       = [[Doug Ford]]\n| term_start    = June 29, 2018\n| term_end      = \n| predecessor   = [[Dipika Damerla]]\n| successor     =\n\n| parliament1   = Ontario Provincial\n| term_start1   = September 1, 2016\n| term_end1     = \n| predecessor1  = [[Bas Balkissoon]]\n| successor1    = \n| riding1       = [[Scarborough North (provincial electoral district)|Scarborough North]]<Br><small>[[Scarborough\u2014Rouge River (provincial electoral district)|Scarborough\u2014Rouge River]] (2016-2018)</small>\n| office2       = [[Toronto City Councillor]] for [[Scarborough\u2014Rouge River|(Ward 42) Scarborough\u2014Rouge River]]\n| term_start2   = December 1, 2000\n| term_end2     = September 10, 2016\n| predecessor2  = ''New ward''\n| successor2    = [[Neethan Shan]]\n| office3      = Chair of the Scarborough Community Council\n| term_start3  = December 1, 2003\n| term_end3    = June 27, 2005\n| predecessor3 = [[Ron Moeser]]\n| successor3   = [[Michael Thompson (Canadian politician)|Michael Thompson]]\n| office4      = [[Toronto City Councillor]] for Scarborough Malvern (Ward 18) \n| term_start4  = January 1, 1998\n| term_end4    = December 1, 2000\n| predecessor4 = ''New ward''\n| successor4   = ''Ward abolished''\n| office5      = [[Metro Toronto|Metro Toronto City Councillor]] for Scarborough Malvern (Ward 18)\n| term_start5  = December 1, 1991\n| term_end5    = January 1, 1998\n| predecessor5 = Bob Sanders\n| successor5   = ''City Amalgamated''\n| party        = [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Progressive Conservative]] <small>(Provincial)</small> <br /> [[Independent politician|Independent]] <small>(Municipal)</small>\n|otherparty    = [[New Democratic Party]] <small><br />(until ca. 1991)</small><br />[[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]<small><br />(mid-1990s-2004)</small>\n| residence    = \n| alma_mater   = [[University of Toronto]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1936|11|18}}\n| birth_place  = [[Seoul]], [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese-Occupied Korea]]<ref name=\"raycho.com\">{{cite web|url=http://raymondcho.com/index.php/about-raymond |title=About Raymond \u2013 Raymond Cho}}</ref>\n| spouse       = Soon Ok<ref name=\"raychopc\" /> \n| children     = 3\n| occupation   = Social Worker\n}}\n'''Raymond Sung Joon Cho''' ([[Korean language|Korean]]: \uc870\uc131\uc900) (born November 18, 1936) is a politician from Ontario who is currently serving as [[Ministry of Seniors Affairs|Minister of Seniors and Accessibility of Ontario]] since June 29, 2018. In 2016, he won a by-election to become the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario]] MPP for [[Scarborough\u2014Rouge River (provincial electoral district)|Scarborough\u2014Rouge River]] in the [[Ontario legislature]]. Previously, he had been a municipal politician since 1991, most recently as a [[Toronto City Council|City Councillor]] representing [[Scarborough\u2014Rouge River|Ward 42 Scarborough\u2014Rouge River]]. Before being elected, he worked as a social worker for the Catholic Children's Aid Society, the [[Toronto Board of Education]], and the Scarborough Board of Education.<ref name=\"raychopc\" />\n\nCho holds a master's degree in Social Work and Doctorate in Education from the [[University of Toronto]]. He is married to Soon Ok, and has three adult sons: Raymond Jr., Ronald, and William.<ref name=\"raychopc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ontariopc.ca/raymond_cho |title=Raymond Cho - MPP, Scarborough-Rouge River|url-status=live |archivedate=June 3, 2017| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603183320/https://www.ontariopc.ca/raymond_cho| publisher=[[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Ontario PC]]}}</ref>\n\n==Municipal politics==\nHe was first elected to [[Metropolitan Toronto]] Council for Scarborough-Malvern in 1991, and was re-elected in 1994.  After the Scarborough and the other suburbs were amalgamated into the new City of Toronto,  Cho was elected to the new council representing Scarborough-Malvern in 1997 along with [[Bas Balkissoon]]. In 2000, he was again re-elected, representing the new ward of Scarborough Rouge-River. He won re-election in 2003, 2006 and 2010.\n\nOn August 13, 2004, the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' reported that Cho spent nearly all of his allotted councillor expense fund, one of the highest on city council. While there was some speculation that some of this money was diverted to Cho's failed bid to run in the federal election campaign, his executive assistant said the money was needed for newsletters mailed out to constituents to provide information on a rash of fatal shootings in the [[Malvern, Toronto|Malvern]] neighbourhood earlier in the year.<ref>Catherine Porter. Cho biggest spender at city hall; $53,100 limit nearly spent Councillor ran in federal election. Toronto Star. August 13, 2004. Pg. F02.</ref>\n\nCho was Chairman of the [[Toronto Zoo]] for two successive terms.\n\n==Federal politics==\nCho was a [[New Democratic Party]] candidate for election to the [[House of Commons of Canada]] in the [[1988 Canadian federal election|1988 federal election]] and was initially identified as a New Democrat when he joined Metro Council, however, he soon became an ally and supporter of then [[Metropolitan Toronto Chairman]] [[Alan Tonks]] and dropped his NDP affiliation. He subsequently took out membership in the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] though, like most non-NDP municipal politicians in [[Ontario]] he did not run on a party label in municipal elections.\n\nHe ran in the [[2004 Canadian federal election|2004 federal election]] as an independent candidate in [[Scarborough\u2014Rouge River]].  Cho called himself an \"independent Liberal\", and used the [[Liberal Party of Canada]]'s red-and-white colours for his campaign materials.  He was accused of trying to mislead voters by the official Liberal candidate, [[Derek Lee (politician)|Derek Lee]]. Lee, who has been the MP since 1988 said that Cho caused some controversy by claiming to have been shut out of the candidate nomination process.<ref>Ho Anderson. Rookies challenge Liberal MP. Toronto Star. June 19, 2004. Pg. H03.</ref> Lee won the election, Cho placed a distant second with 6,692 votes (17.8% of the total).\n\n==Provincial politics==\nIn 2005, Cho expressed interest in being the [[Ontario Liberal Party]]'s candidate in the [[Scarborough\u2014Rouge River]] provincial [[by-election]] which was made necessary by the appointment of incumbent Liberal [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|MPP]] [[Alvin Curling]] to a diplomatic position. However, the Liberal riding association used a clause of its constitution to declare another city councillor, Bas Balkissoon, as its candidate without a contested nomination process. Media reports suggested that this was done to exclude Cho as the provincial riding association was displeased with Cho's \"independent Liberal\" candidacy in the 2004 federal election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressreader.com/canada/toronto-star/20051005/281878703764820| first=Ian| last=Urquhart| title=Liberals play rough on by-election. Toronto Star| date=October 5, 2005| publisher=[[Toronto Star]]| website=pressreader.com}}</ref> Cho was also mentioned as a potential candidate for the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Progressive Conservatives]] since he helped former leader [[John Tory]] during the March 2005 by-election in [[Dufferin\u2014Peel\u2014Wellington\u2014Grey (provincial electoral district)|Dufferin\u2014Peel\u2014Wellington\u2014Grey]].<ref>Robert Benzie. Twice bitten, McGuinty shy of vote; Curling's Scarborough riding considered a safe Liberal seat. Toronto Star. August 27, 2005. Pg F02.</ref> In the end, Cho chose not to run in the by-election which was won handily by Balkissoon.\n\nIn 2012, Cho was named as the Progressive Conservative candidate for the provincial riding of [[Scarborough\u2014Rouge River (provincial electoral district)|Scarborough\u2014Rouge River]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Alcoba |first=Natalie |title=Rob Ford critic Raymond Cho named as Ontario PC candidate for Scarborough-Rouge River |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2012/12/18/rob-ford-critic-raymond-cho-named-as-ontario-pc-candidate-for-scarborough-rouge-river/ |date=18 December 2012|publisher=[[National Post]]}}</ref> In the [[2014 Ontario general election|2014 provincial election]], Cho placed third with 27.68% of the vote.\n\nIn 2016, Cho was nominated as the Progressive Conservative Party candidate for the September 1 by-election in Scarborough\u2014Rouge River, after incumbent Liberal MPP Bas Balkissoon resigned to spend more time with family. Cho won the by-election in an upset victory,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/queenspark/2016/09/01/patrick-browns-sex-ed-snafu-dominates-scarborough-byelection.html| publisher=[[Toronto Star]]| title=Tory Raymond Cho wins Scarborough-Rouge River byelection| first=Robert| last=Benzie |date=September 1, 2016 |url-status=live| archivedate=June 3, 2017| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603184208/https://www.thestar.com/news/queenspark/2016/09/01/patrick-browns-sex-ed-snafu-dominates-scarborough-byelection.html}}</ref> becoming the [[List of visible minority politicians in Canada|first Korean-Canadian]] elected to the Ontario Legislature. Cho was handily reelected in 2018 in the new riding of [[Scarborough North (provincial electoral district)|Scarborough North]], winning over half of the popular vote.\n\n==Election results==\n\n===Federal===\n\n====