rk Jensen''' (registered June 1)\n*'''Glenn Middleton''' (registered January 13)\n*'''Tushar Shah''' (registered September 8)\n*'''Sandip Vora''' (registered August 30)\n\n==Ward 39: Scarborough\u2014Agincourt==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 39''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Mike Del Grande]]''' ||align=right| 9,931 ||align=right| 68.184% \n|-\n|Kevin Xu ||align=right| 3,640 ||align=right| 24.991% \n|-\n|Caldwell Williams ||align=right| 994 ||align=right| 6.825% \n|-\n!Total||align=right| 14,565 ||align=right| 100% \n|}\n\n*'''[[Michael Del Grande]]''' ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/> (incumbent) (registered January 4) First elected in 2003, Del Grande is a founding member of Scarborough Needs Accountable Politicians (SNAP), and has been a member of the Scarborough Homeowners Alliance for Fair Taxes since this group's inception\n*'''Caldwell Williams''' (registered March 10)\n*'''Kevin Xu''' (registered August 27)\n\n==Ward 40: Scarborough\u2014Agincourt==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 40''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Norm Kelly]]''' ||align=right| 12,458 ||align=right| 74.001% \n|-\n|Ken Sy ||align=right| 1,935 ||align=right| 11.494% \n|-\n|Bryan Heal ||align=right| 1,862 ||align=right| 11.06% \n|-\n|Cheng-Chih Tsai ||align=right| 580 ||align=right| 3.445% \n|-\n!Total||align=right| 16,835 ||align=right| 100% \n|}\n\n*'''Bryan Heal''' (registered January 11)\n*'''[[Norm Kelly]]''' ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/>  (incumbent) (registered January 4) Kelly first served on Scarborough Borough Council from 1974 until 1980 when he was elected to the House of Commons as a Liberal MP but was defeated in 1984 and again in 1988. He subsequently returned to municipal politics and was elected to Metro Council for Scarborough in 1994 and Toronto City Council in 1997.\n*'''Ken Sy''' (registered June 28)\n*'''Cheng-Chih Tsai''' (registered September 9)\n\n==Ward 41: Scarborough\u2014Rouge River==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 41''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Chin Lee]]''' ||align=right| 12,557 ||align=right| 70.616% \n|-\n|Patricia Sinclair ||align=right| 2,718 ||align=right| 15.285% \n|-\n|Danny Chien ||align=right| 2,507 ||align=right| 14.099% \n|-\n!Total||align=right| 17,782 ||align=right| 100% \n|}\n\n*'''Danny Chien''' (registered July 7)\n*'''[[Chin Lee]]''' ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/> (incumbent) (registered January 6) Lee was seeking his second term as councillor.\n*'''Patricia Sinclair''' (registered July 14)\n\n==Ward 42: Scarborough\u2014Rouge River==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 42''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Raymond Cho (politician)|Raymond Cho]]''' ||align=right| 10,811 ||align=right| 52.93% \n|-\n|[[Neethan Shan]] ||align=right| 6,873 ||align=right| 33.65% \n|-\n|Shamoon Poonawala ||align=right| 586 ||align=right| 2.869% \n|-\n|Mohammed Ather ||align=right| 474 ||align=right| 2.321% \n|-\n|Namu Ponnambalam ||align=right| 443 ||align=right| 2.169% \n|-\n|Ruth Tecle ||align=right| 437 ||align=right| 2.14% \n|-\n|George Singh ||align=right| 353 ||align=right| 1.728% \n|-\n|Leon Saul ||align=right| 323 ||align=right| 1.581% \n|-\n|Venthan Ramanathavavuniyan ||align=right| 125 ||align=right| 0.612% \n|-\n!Total||align=right| 20,425 ||align=right| 100% \n|}\n\n*'''Mohammed Ather''' (registered January 6)\n*'''[[Raymond Cho (politician)|Raymond Cho]]''' ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/>  (incumbent) (registered January 14) Cho, 74, is a social worker by training and was first elected to Scarborough City Council in 1991 and has served on Toronto City Council since 1997. He has been active in both the New Democratic Party and the Liberal Party.\n*'''Namu Ponnambalam''' (registered February 18)\n*'''Shamoon Poonawala''' (registered January 4)\n*'''Venthan Ramanathavavuniyan''' (registered April 19)\n*'''Leon Saul''' (registered August 4)\n*'''Neethan Shan''' (registered January 4)\n*'''George Singh''' (registered September 7)\n*'''Ruth Tecle''' (registered June 22)\n\n==Ward 43: Scarborough East==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 43''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Paul Ainslie]]''' ||align=right| 9,334 ||align=right| 60.559% \n|-\n|John Laforet ||align=right| 4,440 ||align=right| 28.807% \n|-\n|Bhaskar Sharma ||align=right| 758 ||align=right| 4.918% \n|-\n|Benjamin Mbaegbu ||align=right| 489 ||align=right| 3.173% \n|-\n|Samuel Getachew ||align=right| 392 ||align=right| 2.543% \n|-\n!Total||align=right| 15,413 ||align=right| 100% \n|}\n\n*'''[[Paul Ainslie]]'''  ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/> (incumbent) (registered January 4) Ainslie has been a city councillor since 2003 and was previously executive assistant to [[David Soknacki]].\n*'''Samuel Getachew''' (registered February 18) Getachew is a community builder and activist. He has worked on many campaigns including the then Senator Barack Obama's presidential campaign in Ohio and Pennsylvania. His writings have appeared in the ''Toronto Sun'', Tzta, Sway magazine, Metro Daily and the ''Ottawa Citizen'' among others.\n*'''John Laforet''' (registered January 15) Laforet lives in Ward 43 and has been a local community activist for years on issues ranging from historical preservation to opposition to Toronto Hydro's offshore wind proposal. He is the President of Wind Concerns Ontario.\n*'''Benjamin Mbaegbu''' (registered April 8) Mbaegbu ran for Mayor of Toronto in 2003, garnering 288 votes. In 2001 he sought election in Ward 31's by-election.\n*'''Bhaskar Sharma''' (registered July 21) Sharma has a background in media and has been the publisher of a well-circulated paper for the last twenty-five years.\n\n==Ward 44: Scarborough East==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 44''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Ron Moeser]]''' ||align=right| 10,185 ||align=right| 47.456% \n|-\n|Diana Hall ||align=right| 9,901 ||align=right| 46.133% \n|-\n|Mohammed Mirza ||align=right| 749 ||align=right| 3.49% \n|-\n|Heath Thomas ||align=right| 627 ||align=right| 2.921% \n|-\n!Total||align=right| 21,462 ||align=right| 100% \n|}\n\n*'''Diana Hall''' (registered January 4) Hall was the runner-up in the 2006 election losing to Ron Moeser by 61 votes.\n*'''Mohammed Mirza''' (registered September 8)\n*'''[[Ron Moeser]]''' ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/> (incumbent) (registered February 2) Moeser was first elected to Scarborough city council in 1988 and then Toronto city council in 1997. He was defeated in 2003 by [[Gay Cowbourne]] but returned to office in 2006 when Cowbourne retired, defeating Diana Hall by 61 votes.\n*'''Heath Thomas''' (registered January 18)\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.toronto.ca/elections/index.htm City of Toronto election webpage]\n\n{{Toronto elections}}\n\n[[Category:Municipal elections in Toronto|2010]]\n[[Category:2010 Ontario municipal elections]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|information about the election for mayor|Toronto mayoral election, 2010}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2010 Toronto municipal election\n| country            = Toronto\n| type               = Municipal\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 2006 Toronto municipal election\n| previous_year      = 2006\n| next_election      = 2014 Toronto municipal election\n| next_year          = 2014\n| election_date      = October 25, 2010\n| image1             = \n| color1             = \n| candidate1         = \n| popular_vote1      = \n| percentage1        = \n| image2             =  \n| color2             = \n| candidate2         = \n| popular_vote2      = \n| percentage2        = \n| image3             = \n| candidate3         =  \n| color3             =  \n| popular_vote3      = \n| percentage3        = \n| map_image          = Torontowards.PNG\n| map_size           = 350px\n| map_caption        = The ward boundaries for the 2010 election. The Mayor and French school board trustees are elected across the city, councillors in their respective wards, and English public and Catholic trustees on a ward or dual-ward basis.\n}}\n\nThe '''municipal election''' was held on October 25, 2010 to elect a [[Mayor of Toronto|mayor]] and 44 [[Toronto City Council|city councillors]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. In addition, school trustees were elected to the [[Toronto District School Board]], [[Toronto Catholic District School Board]], [[Conseil scolaire de district du Centre-Sud-Ouest]] and [[Conseil scolaire de district catholique Centre-Sud]]. The election was held in conjunction with those held in other municipalities in the province of [[Ontario]] (see [[2010 Ontario municipal elections]]). Candidate registration opened on January 4, 2010 and ended on September 10. Advance polls were open October 5, 6, 7, 8 and 12, 13, 16 and 17.\n\nThere were a number of open seats as two sitting councillors, [[Rob Ford]] and [[Joe Pantalone]], ran for mayor, while incumbents [[Case Ootes]], [[Kyle Rae]], [[Adam Giambrone]], [[Michael Walker (politician)|Michael Walker]], [[Mike Feldman]], [[Brian Ashton (politician)|Brian Ashton]], and [[Howard Moscoe]] did not seek re-election. This was the first election to take place in Toronto since the enactment of a new fund raising by-law whereby unions and corporations could not donate to candidates. The nomination period for the 2010 municipal election opened on Monday, January 4, 2010 and closed on Friday, September 10, 2010.\n\nIn the 2010 election, a record number of women was elected to council, with 15 female councillors comprising exactly one third of all council members.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/article/881530--porter-female-breakthrough-on-toronto-city-council?bn=1 \"Porter: Female breakthrough on Toronto city council\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', October 27, 2010.</ref>\n\nWith this election, voting day moved to the fourth Monday of October from the second Monday of November which had been election day since [[1978 Toronto municipal election|1978]].\n\n==Mayor==\n{{Main|Toronto mayoral election, 2010}}\nThe mayor's seat was open for the first time since the [[2003 Toronto municipal election|2003 Toronto election]], due to the announcement by incumbent mayor [[David Miller (Canadian politician)|David Miller]] that he would not seek a third term in office. At the end of the campaign there were three major candidates who were included by the media in public opinion polls and mayoral debates: winner [[Rob Ford]], [[Joe Pantalone]], and [[George Smitherman]].<ref>David Rider \"[https://www.thestar.com/yourcitymycity/article/796057--ford-surges-into-second-place-in-mayoral-poll?bn=1 Ford surges into second place in mayoral poll]\" ''[[Toronto Star]]'' Fri Apr 16 2010</ref><ref>Marcus Gee \"[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/toronto/torontos-mayoral-candidates-face-off-for-the-first-time/article1516056/ Toronto's mayoral candidates face off for the first time]\" ''The Globe and Mail.'' Mar. 29, 2010</ref> Four other candidates, [[Rocco Rossi]], [[Sarah Thomson (politician)|Sarah Thomson]], [[Adam Giambrone]] and [[Giorgio Mammoliti]], were considered major candidates when they launched their campaigns but later dropped out of the campaign.\n\n==City council==\nCity councillors were elected to represent Toronto's 44 wards at [[Toronto City Council]]. There were a number of open seats, as sitting councillors Joe Pantalone and Rob Ford chose to run for mayor, while long-serving incumbents [[Case Ootes]], [[Kyle Rae]], [[Adam Giambrone]], [[Mike Feldman]], [[Michael Walker (politician)|Michael Walker]], [[Brian Ashton (politician)|Brian Ashton]] and [[Howard Moscoe]] announced their retirements.\n\nFive incumbent councillors were defeated, in wards 1, 13, 25, 32, and 35:. [[Vincent Crisanti]] beat [[Suzan Hall]], [[Sarah Doucette]] beat [[Bill Saundercook]], [[Jaye Robinson]] beat [[Cliff Jenkins]], [[Mary-Margaret McMahon]] beat [[Sandra Bussin]], and [[Michelle Berardinetti]] beat [[Adrian Heaps]] respectively.\n\n==School boards==\nSchool trustees were elected to the [[Toronto District School Board]], [[Toronto Catholic District School Board]], [[Conseil scolaire de district du Centre-Sud-Ouest]] and [[Conseil scolaire de district catholique Centre-Sud]].\n\n==Participation initiatives==\nContinuing a tradition established by [[City Idol]] in 2006, grassroots activist groups established a number of initiatives to encourage greater interest and participation in municipal politics.\n\nOne notable initiative in 2010 was Better Ballots, an advocacy group which sponsored a debate concerning municipal voting reform on June 1. Preparations for that debate included an online ballot to name two of the \"minor\" mayoral candidates to the debate panel, in addition to the six \"major\" ones. The winners of the online vote were Rocco Achampong and [[Keith Cole (artist)|Keith Cole]].<ref>[http://www.insidetoronto.com/news/cityhall/article/828239--better-ballots-hosts-mayor-s-debate \"Better Ballots hosts mayor's debate\"]. insidetoronto.com, June 3, 2010.</ref> When Giorgio Mammoliti withdrew from the mayoral race on July 5, he singled out Achampong as a candidate who \"needs to be heard\", and asked the media to give Achampong his former space in the debates.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/832088--mammoliti-quits-mayoral-race?bn=1 \"Mammoliti quits mayoral race\"], ''Toronto Star'', July 5, 2010</ref>\n\nAnother initiative was So You Think You Can Council, an event hosted by comedian [[Maggie Cassella]] which featured Ward 27's council candidates answering questions about Toronto's municipal government in a [[game show]] format.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/822121--so-you-think-you-can-council \"So You Think You Can Council?\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', June 10, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Satire==\nThe campaign was also noted for the creation of two mock campaigns which posted [[satire|satirical]] comments on the election through [[social networking]] platforms. ''Murray4Mayor'' was spearheaded by ''[[National Post]]'' cartoonist [[Chip Zdarsky|Steve Murray]],<ref>[http://torontoist.com/2010/10/steve_murray_hates_toronto_and_wants_to_be_your_mayor.php \"Steve Murray Hates Toronto, and Wants to Be Your Mayor\"]. Torontoist, October 1, 2010.</ref> while ''The Rebel Mayor'', which was eventually revealed as the creation of journalist Shawn Micallef, was written in the persona of 19th century Toronto mayor [[William Lyon Mackenzie]].<ref>[https://archive.today/20120913052541/http://www.torontolife.com/daily/informer/mayor-may-not/2010/05/20/the-best-of-rebel-mayor-the-funniest-quips-f rom-city-halls-mystery-tweeter-who-was-unmasked-sort-of-this-week/ \"The best of Rebel Mayor: the funniest quips from city hall\u2019s mystery tweeter, who was unmasked (sort of) this week\"]. ''[[Toronto Life]]'', May 20, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Ward 9 York Centre and TDSB Ward 4 election irregularities==\nOn March 29, 2011, a judge of the [[Ontario Superior Court of Justice]] invalidated the election results for Ward 9 and [[Toronto District School Board|TDSB]] Ward 4 because of \"several \u201cirregularities\u201d in the voters list\". The civil lawsuit was brought forward by Gus Cusimano. He lost by 89 votes and was the runner-up. There were missing signatures of electoral officers on 426 of 1,143 forms that allowed election-day changes to the voter list.<ref name=\"Ward9-4invalidation\">{{cite news|title=By-election ordered for Augimeri's Ward 9 York Centre and TDSB Ward 4 |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/toronto/by-election-ordered-for-augimeris-ward-9-york-centre-and-tdsb-ward-4/article1994883/ |accessdate=21 April 2011 |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=21 April 2011 |location=Toronto |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110423093122/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/toronto/by-election-ordered-for-augimeris-ward-9-york-centre-and-tdsb-ward-4/article1994883/ |archivedate=April 23, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite news | last = Nickle | first = David | title = Ward 9 to be challenged in court | work = Inside Toronto | pages = | publisher = Toronto Community News | date = 2011-02-04 | url = http://www.insidetoronto.com/news/cityhall/article/938899--ward-9-to-be-challenged-in-court | accessdate = 2011-02-16 }}</ref>\n\nInitially the city's legal staff said they would be appealing the decision but on May 13 it was announced that the city would not launch an appeal. City Clerk, Uli Watkiss said in a statement, \"The decision to proceed with a by-election and resolve this matter as quickly as possible is in the best interest of the public, the individuals directly affected, and the workings of Council.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = Augimeri to face new vote | work = CBC Toronto | publisher = Canadian Broadcasting Company | date = 2011-05-13 | url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/story/2011/05/13/toronto-byelection.html | accessdate = 2011-08-14}}</ref> The mayor's office supported the decision. [[Rob Ford]]'s press secretary [[Adrienne Batra]] said, \"Obviously the mayor supported (Cusimano) during the general election and once the by-election gets under way he will be fully supporting him again.\"<ref>{{cite news | first = Don | last = Peat |title = Byelection a go in Augimeri's Ward 9  | publisher = Toronto Sun | date = 2011-05-13 | url = http://www.torontosun.com/2011/05/13/byelection-a-go-in-augimeris-ward-9 | accessdate = 2011-08-14}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, [[Maria Augimeri]] announced that she would be appealing the decision herself. She said the by-election would cost $525,000.<ref group=\"nb\">The cost of the ward 9 by-election is estimated at $175,000. The court decision also affected a school trustee election and that election would cost $350,000 since it spans two wards.</ref> She said, \"The clerk\u2019s advice not to appeal does harm to taxpayers as well as to the integrity of our electoral system.\"<ref>{{cite news |last = Alcoba |first = Natalie | title = Councillor Augimeri to appeal byelection decision | work = | publisher = National Post | date = 2011-05-16 | url = http://news.nationalpost.com/2011/05/16/councillor-augimeri-to-appeal-by-election-decision/ | accessdate = 2011-08-14}}</ref> On August 4, the city reversed its decision and decided to join the appeal which will be held in September 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last = Rider |first = David | title = Mississauga asks to join Augimeri-Cusimano appeal | work = Toronto Star | publisher = TorStar | date = 2011-08-04 | url = https://www.thestar.com/news/article/1034651 | accessdate = 2011-08-14}}</ref> On December 19, the court ruled in Augimeri's favour. A three judge panel ruled that although 300 ballots were unsigned by electoral officers the people voting were very likely eligible to vote and that this would have no effect on the election. In a related judgement, they also ruled that Cusimano incorrectly voted in the Ward 9 election because he lived in another riding. They decided that no further action was necessary.<ref>{{cite news |last = Dale |first = Daniel | title = Ward 9 byelection rejected, Augimeri to stay | work = Toronto Star | publisher = TorStar | date = 2011-12-19 | url = https://www.thestar.com/news/cityhallpolitics/article/1104537 | accessdate = 2011-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Ward 1: Etobicoke North==\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 1''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Vincent Crisanti]]'''||align=right| 5,505||align=right| 40.736% \n|-\n|[[Suzan Hall]] ||align=right|4,996||align=right| 36.969% \n|-\n|Omar Farouk ||align=right|1,573||align=right| 11.64% \n|-\n|Sharad Sharma ||align=right|883||align=right| 6.534% \n|-\n|Ted Berger ||align=right|388 ||align=right|2.871% \n|-\n|Peter D'Gama ||align=right|169 ||align=right|1.251% \n|-\n!Total||align=right|13,514 ||align=right|100% \n|}\n\n*'''Ted Berger''' (registered March 23)\n*'''[[Vincent Crisanti]]''' ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\">[http://www.cbc.ca/toronto/features/torontovotes2010/ CBA.ca Toronto Votes]</ref> (registered June 15)\n*'''Peter D'Gama''' (registered July 20)\n*'''Omar Farouk''' (registered June 8)\n*'''[[Suzan Hall]]'''  (incumbent) (registered January 4) Hall was running for re-election and had been on city council since 2000. Prior to that she was a school trustee.<ref name=usual>[http://www.torontosun.com/news/torontoandgta/2010/01/05/12349521-sun.html \"Usual suspects line up for municipal vote\"], ''Toronto Sun'', January 5, 2010</ref>\n*'''Sharad Sharma''' (registered February 5)\n\n==Ward 2: Etobicoke North==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 2''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Doug Ford]]'''||align=right| 12,660 ||align=right| 71.679% \n|-\n|Cadigia Ali ||align=right| 2,346 ||align=right| 13.283% \n|-\n|Luciano Rizzuti ||align=right| 828 ||align=right| 4.688% \n|-\n|Rajinder Lall ||align=right| 736 ||align=right| 4.167% \n|-\n|Andrew Saikaley ||align=right| 637 ||align=right| 3.607% \n|-\n|Jason Pedlar ||align=right| 455 ||align=right| 2.576% \n|-\n!Total||align=right| 17,662 ||align=right|  100% \n|}\n\nThe seat was open because incumbent [[Rob Ford]] ran for mayor.\n*'''Cadigia Ali''' (registered June 4) Ali was the runner-up in this ward in the last election. She is a health professional (Rexdale Community Health Centre) and activist (Etobicoke Conflict Mediation Team).<ref name=eyew>{{cite news|last=Porter|first=Catherine|title=Porter: City council hopefuls are just what Toronto needs|url=https://www.thestar.com/yourtoronto/yourcitymycity/2010/03/16/porter_city_council_hopefuls_are_just_what_toronto_needs.html|accessdate=19 December 2013|newspaper=The Star|date=16 March 2010}}</ref>\n*'''[[Doug Ford]]''' ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/>(registered August 9) Doug Ford, 45, is Rob Ford's brother and campaign manager.  He is president of [[Deco Labels]], a family owned business founded by [[Doug Ford Sr.|his father]].<ref>[http://www.torontosun.com/news/torontoandgta/2010/08/05/14936011.html \"Rob Ford's brother joins race\"], ''Toronto Sun'', August 5, 2010</ref>\n*'''Rajinder Lall''' (registered July 27); Etobicoke real estate broker\n*'''Jason Pedlar''' (registered June 18); mediator with the Financial Services Commission of Ontario\n*'''Luciano Rizzuti''' (registered September 10)\n*'''Andrew Saikaley''' (registered April 13);  transportation consultant\n\n==Ward 3: Etobicoke Centre==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 3''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Doug Holyday]]'''||align=right|13,521 ||align=right|71.92% \n|-\n|-\n||Peter Kudryk ||align=right|2,684 ||align=right|14.277% \n|-\n|Ross Vaughan ||align=right|1,585 ||align=right|8.431% \n|-\n|Roger Deschenes ||align=right|1,010 ||align=right|5.372% \n|-\n!Total||align=right|18,800 ||align=right|100% \n|}\n\n*'''Roger Deschenes''' (registered April 26) Roger Deschenes, a candidate for Ward 3 in the 2010 Toronto elections, has lived his entire life in the city of Toronto. Deschenes was raised in downtown Toronto and has lived in Ward 3 for the past 22 years. Previously self-employed in the food industry, Deschenes also has years of experience in construction.\n*'''[[Doug Holyday]]'''  ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/> (incumbent) (registered June 30) Holyday has been councillor since 1998. He was Etobicoke City Councillor (1986\u20131994) and mayor (1994\u20131997), and Metro Toronto councillor (1994\u20131997).\n*'''Peter Kudryk''' (registered March 22)\n\n==Ward 4: Etobicoke Centre==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 4''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Gloria Lindsay Luby]]''' ||align=right| 9,789 ||align=right| 46.902% \n|-\n|[[John Campbell (Ontario politician)|John Campbell]] ||align=right| 9,480 ||align=right| 45.422% \n|-\n|Daniel Bertolini ||align=right| 1,602 ||align=right| 7.676% \n|-\n!Total||align=right| 20,871 ||align=right|  100% \n|}\n\n*'''Daniel Bertolini''' (registered September 10)\n*'''John Campbell''' (registered July 8)\n*'''[[Gloria Lindsay Luby]]'''  ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/> (incumbent) (registered March 8) Luby was a school trustee before being elected to [[Etobicoke]] city council. She was elected to Toronto City Council in 1997 when the Etobicoke was amalgamated into the new city of Toronto.\n\n==Ward 5: Etobicoke\u2014Lakeshore==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 5''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Peter Milczyn]]''' ||align=right|9,778 ||align=right|41.16% \n|-\n|[[Justin Di Ciano]] ||align=right|9,669 ||align=right| 40.701% \n|-\n|[[Morley Kells]] ||align=right|2,725 ||align=right|11.471% \n|-\n|John Chiappetta ||align=right|1,245 ||align=right|5.241% \n|-\n|Rob Therrien ||align=right|339 ||align=right|1.427% \n|-\n!Total||align=right|23,756 ||align=right|100% \n|}\n\n*'''John Chiappetta''' (registered September 10)\n*'''Justin Di Ciano''' (registered July 12)\n*'''[[Morley Kells]]''' (registered September 8) Kells was an Etobicoke councillor and [[Board of Control (municipal government)|Controller]] in the 1970s and then served as Progressive Conservative MPP from 1981 to 1985 and again from 1995 to 2003. He was Minister of the Environment in [[Frank Miller (politician)|Frank Miller]]'s short-lived government.\n*'''[[Peter Milczyn]]''' ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/> (incumbent) (registered January 14) First elected in 1994 to Etobicoke City Council. Defeated in 1997 in the first post-amalgamation election. Elected to Toronto City Council in 2000.\n*'''Rob Thierrien''' (registered September 10)\n\n==Ward 6: Etobicoke\u2014Lakeshore==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 6''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Mark Grimes]]''' ||align=right| 12,228 ||align=right| 60.421% \n|-\n|Jem Cain ||align=right| 5,847 ||align=right| 28.891% \n|-\n|[[Michael Laxer]] ||align=right| 717 ||align=right| 3.543% \n|-\n|Wendell Brereton ||align=right| 605 ||align=right| 2.989% \n|-\n|Cecilia Luu ||align=right| 466 ||align=right| 2.303% \n|-\n|David Searle ||align=right| 375 ||align=right| 1.853% \n|-\n!Total||align=right| 20,238 ||align=right|  100% \n|}\n\n*'''Wendell Brereton''' (registered August 4) A pastor who describes himself as a fundamentalist Christian, Brereton was a candidate for mayor but withdrew in July to endorse Rob Ford. Brereton, a former officer with the [[Ontario Provincial Police]], is a social conservative who opposes same-sex marriage. He supports government stimulus spending to combat the recession.<ref>[http://www.torontosun.com/news/torontoandgta/2010/08/05/14935591.html \"Politics, not religion, unite Ford, Brereton\"], ''Toronto Sun'', August 5, 2010</ref>\n*'''Jem Cain''' (registered January 4) Cain was also a candidate in the 2006 municipal election.\n*'''[[Mark Grimes]]''' ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/> (incumbent) (registered August 11) A former trader on the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]], Grimes was first elected to Toronto City Council in 2003.\n*'''[[Michael Laxer]]''' (registered July 2) Laxer is a local used book store owner and community activist and a former candidate for the [[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democratic Party]] at both the federal and provincial level.\n*'''David Searle''' (registered August 31) Searle, who describes himself as a [[Red Tory]], and also ran for council in the [[2003 Toronto municipal election|2003 municipal election]] and opposes the intwining of church and state. He is a supporter of the Ontario Progressive Conservative Party and is a moderate on social issues.\n\n==Ward 7: York West==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 7''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Giorgio Mammoliti]]''' ||align=right| 5,338 ||align=right| 43.797% \n|-\n|Nick Di Nizio ||align=right| 3,601 ||align=right| 29.545% \n|-\n|Victor Lucero ||align=right| 1,038 ||align=right| 8.517% \n|-\n|Sergio Gizzo ||align=right| 706 ||align=right| 5.793% \n|-\n|Sharon Joseph ||align=right| 547 ||align=right| 4.488% \n|-\n|Chris MacDonald ||align=right| 491 ||align=right| 4.029% \n|-\n|Larry Perlman ||align=right| 249 ||align=right| 2.043% \n|-\n|Scott Aitchison ||align=right| 129 ||align=right| 1.058% \n|-\n|Stefano Tesoro ||a