band of comedian [[Carla Collins]]. He was endorsed by former Ontario PC leader, [[John Tory]].<ref name=eyew/>\n*'''Mohamed Dhanani''' (registered February 26) Dhanani was the runner-up in the 2006 election.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://kscheuer.wordpress.com/2010/03/01/mohamed-dhanani-rematch-with-parker/ |title = Mohamed Dhanani rematch with Parker|date = March 2010}}</ref>\n*'''Nawab Salim Khan''' (registered July 29)\n*'''Shaukat Malik''' (registered June 14)\n*'''Yunus Pandor''' (registered July 12)\n*'''[[John Parker (Canadian politician)|John Parker]]''' ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/> (incumbent) (registered January 4) Parker was the area's [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Progressive Conservative]] MPP at [[Ontario legislature|Queen's Park]] from 1995 to 1999. He was first elected to Toronto city council in 2006 with approximately 20% of the vote.\n\n==Ward 27: Toronto Centre==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 27''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Kristyn Wong-Tam]]''' ||align=right| 7,527 ||align=right| 28.277% \n|-\n|Ken Chan ||align=right| 7,065 ||align=right| 26.541% \n|-\n|Chris Tindal ||align=right| 3,447 ||align=right| 12.949% \n|-\n|Simon Wookey ||align=right| 2,128 ||align=right| 7.994% \n|-\n|Joel Dick ||align=right| 1,667 ||align=right| 6.262% \n|-\n|Robert Meynell ||align=right| 1,223 ||align=right| 4.594% \n|-\n|Enza Anderson ||align=right| 1,127 ||align=right| 4.234% \n|-\n|Ella Rebanks ||align=right| 838 ||align=right| 3.148% \n|-\n|Ben Bergen ||align=right| 380 ||align=right| 1.428% \n|-\n|Susan Gapka ||align=right| 367 ||align=right| 1.379% \n|-\n|Gary Leroux ||align=right| 283 ||align=right| 1.063% \n|-\n|Paul Spence ||align=right| 243 ||align=right| 0.913% \n|-\n|Jonas Jemstone ||align=right| 142 ||align=right| 0.533% \n|-\n|Ram Narula ||align=right| 108 ||align=right| 0.406% \n|-\n|Perry Missal ||align=right| 74 ||align=right| 0.278% \n|-\n!Total||align=right| 26,619 ||align=right| 100% \n|}\n\nVeteran councillor [[Kyle Rae]], who held a seat on council since 1991, announced that he would not be running for re-election.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/737918--council-veteran-kyle-rae-won-t-run-for-re-election?bn=1 \"Council veteran Kyle Rae won't run for re-election\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', December 11, 2009.</ref>\n*'''[[Enza Anderson]]''' (registered January 20) Anderson, a well-known local transgender personality, was a candidate for [[Mayor of Toronto]] in the [[2000 Toronto municipal election|2000 election]], and a candidate for Ward 27 councillor in the [[2003 Toronto municipal election|2003 election]] finishing second to Rae.<ref>[http://www.cp24.com/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20091125/091125_enza_anderson/20091125/?hub=CP24Home \"Enza Anderson to run for city council in 2010\"]. [[CP24]], November 25, 2009.</ref>\n*'''Ben Bergen''' (registered September 10) Bergen is completing a degree in political science and economics at the University of Toronto. His platform included proposals for a congestion tax to fund transit expansion and bike paths to reduce pollution and traffic.<ref name=\"votebenbergen.ca\">{{cite web |url=http://votebenbergen.ca/wordpress/issues-policy/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-01-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101021111304/http://votebenbergen.ca/wordpress/issues-policy/ |archivedate=2010-10-21 }}</ref> Bergen also supported building more public spaces in Ward 27, such as a summertime boardwalk on Church Street.<ref name=\"votebenbergen.ca\"/>\n*'''Ken Chan''' (registered February 23) Chan is a former [[Peel Regional Police]] officer who later served in the offices of then Health Minister [[George Smitherman]] and London (England) Mayor [[Boris Johnson]] as a policy advisor.<ref>[http://www.torontoelectionnews.com/2010/01/12/exclusive-former-cop-uk-advisor-running-to-replace-rae/ \"Former Cop, UK Advisor Running to Replace Rae\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717075657/http://www.torontoelectionnews.com/2010/01/12/exclusive-former-cop-uk-advisor-running-to-replace-rae/ |date=2011-07-17 }}, January 12, 2010.</ref> He was endorsed by outgoing councillor [[Kyle Rae]],<ref name=nowcand/> [[Toronto District School Board|school board trustees]] Sheila Ward and Nadia Bello, [[Ryerson University]] President [[Sheldon Levy]], [[Don Valley West]] MP [[Rob Oliphant]], councillors [[Case Ootes]] and [[Karen Stintz]], former Liberal provincial ministers [[Bob Wong]] and [[Charles Beer]], former NDP provincial minister [[Andrew Thomson (Canadian politician)|Andrew Thomson]], prominent constitutional lawyer Douglas Elliott, and former Principal Secretary to [[Mike Harris]] Stewart Braddick.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.votekenchan.ca/endorsements.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-01-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313181702/http://www.votekenchan.ca/endorsements.html |archivedate=2012-03-13 }}</ref> He campaigned on investing in the arts community.<ref name=stars10/>\n*'''Joel Dick''' (registered February 3) Dick is a lawyer and community activist. He was a candidate for Ward 14 (Toronto Centre) [[Toronto District School Board]] Trustee in the [[2006 Toronto municipal election|2006 election]] and is active with the New Democratic Party.  He is endorsed by federal NDP candidate for Toronto Centre Susan Wallace, former provincial NDP candidate for Toronto Centre Helen Breslauer, [[Canadian Union of Public Employees|CUPE]] 4400 and the Central Ontario Building Trades union.\n*'''Susan Gapka''' (registered January 21) Gapka serves on the executive of the [[Ontario New Democratic Party]] as an [[LGBT]] representative and is a local [[Transexual|Trans]] advocate and past candidate for council.<ref>[http://www.xtra.ca/blog/national/post/2010/01/21/Crowded-race-to-replace-Kyle-Rae-in-Torontos-Ward-27.aspx \"Crowded race to replace Kyle Rae in Toronto's Ward 27\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124085757/http://www.xtra.ca/blog/national/post/2010/01/21/Crowded-race-to-replace-Kyle-Rae-in-Torontos-Ward-27.aspx |date=2010-01-24 }} January 30, 2010.</ref>\n*'''Matthew Over''' (registered September 9)\n*'''Jonas Jemstone''' (registered September 9)\n*'''Robert Meynell''' (registered April 6) Meynell is the author of ''Canadian Idealism and the Philosophy of Freedom.'' McGill-Queen's University Press, 2011. He is a government relations associate at March of Dimes Canada and a lecturer in politics at [[Trent University]] and a successful real estate investor. He was endorsed by [[Hal Jackman]], [[Ila Bossons]], [[Norman Atkins]] and [[Michael Chong]]. He campaigned on fiscal accountability, improving and expanding the TTC, and protecting parks.\n*'''Perry Missal''' (registered February 12)\n*'''Ram Narula''' (registered September 10)\n*'''Ella Rebanks''' (registered February 18)\n*'''Paul Spence ''' (registered January 12)\n*'''Chris Tindal''' (registered January 19) Tindal was the [[Green Party of Canada]] candidate in Toronto Centre in the [[2006 Canadian federal election|2006 federal election]], and in the [[By-elections to the 39th Canadian Parliament#Toronto Centre|2008 by-election]]<ref>[http://www.christindal.ca/2010/01/19/media-release-seasoned-candidate-enters-race-for-councillor-of-ward-27/ \"Seasoned candidate enters race for councillor of Ward 27\"], January 19, 2010.</ref>\n*'''Kristyn Wong-Tam''' ''elected''<ref name=\"cbc\"/> (registered March 1) Wong-Tam is a real estate agent and community activist<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/politics-not-as-usual-in-ward-27/article1483824/ \"Politics not as usual in Ward 27\"]. ''The Globe and Mail'', February 27, 2010.</ref> who was also the registered owner of the website of the group [[Queers Against Israeli Apartheid]].<ref>Toronto Sun, Tuesday September 23, 2010, \"The Other Face of Ward 27 Frontrunner\" by Sue-Ann Levy, http://www.torontosun.com/comment/columnists/sueann_levy/2010/09/23/15457101.html</ref> Wong-Tam has received the endorsement of the powerful Toronto and York Labour Council which includes CUPE<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/toronto/inside-city-hall/reading-the-labour-council-tea-leaves/article1641147/ \"Reading the Labour Council tea leaves\"]. ''The Globe and Mail'', July 15, 2010.</ref>   She was supported by neighbouring councillor [[Adam Vaughan]], former NDP candidate [[Cathy Crowe]] and [[Michele Landsberg]].<ref name=nowcand>[http://www.nowtoronto.com/guides/voteto/2010/story.cfm?content=176552 \"Rating the races\"], ''Now Magazine'', September 2\u20139</ref> She was an advisor to Mayor David Miller on economic development.<ref name=stars10/>\n*'''Simon Wookey''' (registered January 11) Wookey was a candidate for Ward 18 councillor in the [[2006 Toronto municipal election|2006 election]] and is a [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] campaigner<ref>http://wookey.ca/index.php/whotopmenu/42-biographycategory/51-biographyarticle{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, January 30, 2010.</ref> who was endorsed by former provincial treasurer [[Greg Sorbara]].<ref name=nowcand/>\n\n==Ward 28: Toronto Centre==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''Ward 28''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''[[Pam McConnell]]''' ||align=right| 11,883 ||align=right| 62.856% \n|-\n|Howard Bortenstein ||align=right| 3,730 ||align=right| 19.73% \n|-\n|Dennis Hollingsworth ||align=right| 1,128 ||align=right| 5.967% \n|-\n|Raj Rama ||align=right| 969 ||align=right| 5.126% \n|-\n|Daniel Murton ||align=right| 633 ||align=right| 3.348% \n|-\n|Eric Brazau ||align=right| 562 ||