{"title_page": "Adam Vaughan", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| image            = Adam Vaughan - 2017 Homelessness Summit (32445688516) (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Vaughan in 2017\n| honorific-suffix ={{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP|size=100%}}\n| office1           = [[Parliamentary Secretary]] to the [[Minister of Families, Children and Social Development]] (Housing)\n| minister1         = [[Jean-Yves Duclos]]\n| term_start1       = January 30, 2017\n| term_end1         = \n| predecessor1      = [[Terry Duguid]]\n| successor1        =\n\n| office2           = [[Parliamentary Secretary]] to the [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] (Intergovernmental Affairs)\n| minister2         = [[Justin Trudeau]]\n| term_start2       = December 2, 2015\n| term_end2         = January 27, 2017\n| predecessor2      = [[Paul Calandra]]\n| successor2        = [[Peter Schiefke]]\n\n| riding3            = [[Spadina-Fort York]]<br /><small>[[Trinity\u2014Spadina]] (2014-2015)</small>\n| parliament3        = Canadian\n| term_start3        = June 30, 2014\n| term_end3          =\n| predecessor3       = [[Olivia Chow]]\n| successor3         =\n| office4          = [[Toronto City Councillor]] for [[Trinity-Spadina|(Ward 20) Trinity-Spadina]]\n| term_start4      = December 1, 2006\n| term_end4        = May 13, 2014\n| predecessor4     = [[Martin Silva]]\n| successor4       = [[Ceta Ramkhalawansingh]]\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1961|7|3}}\n| birth_place      = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]. Canada\n| nationality      = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| occupation       = Journalist\n}}\n'''Adam Vaughan''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP}} (born July 3, 1961) is a politician in [[Ontario]], Canada. He is a [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member of the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] in the federal government who was elected in a [[By-elections to the 41st Canadian Parliament|by-election]] on June 30, 2014. He is currently the MP for [[Spadina\u2014Fort York]], and the [[Parliamentary Secretary]] to the  [[Minister of Families, Children and Social Development]] (Housing and Urban Affairs). From 2006 to 2014 he was a Toronto city councillor who represented Ward 20 [[Trinity\u2014Spadina]]. Prior to his career in politics he was a radio and TV journalist.\n\n==Background==\nHe is married to Nicole Anatol and he has a son (Salvador) and a daughter (Mimi) from previous relationships. Mimi's mother is journalist [[Suhana Meharchand]].<ref name=kuitenbrouwer>Kuitenbrouwer, P. May 18, 2006. [http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/toronto/story.html?id=8728595a-2455-45f4-a13d-7641487ff9f3 \"No longer a journalist, now candidate for council\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060830230121/http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/toronto/story.html?id=8728595a-2455-45f4-a13d-7641487ff9f3 |date=August 30, 2006 }}. ''[[National Post]]''. Retrieved June 1, 2007.</ref> His father, [[Colin Vaughan]], was a noted architect, television journalist and former city councillor, who preceded Adam as [[City (TV network)|Citytv's]] political reporter until his death in 2000.\n\n==Journalism==\nAdam Vaughan worked at [[Ryerson University]] radio station [[CKLN-FM|CKLN]] from 1982 to 1987, and was manager of the station from 1985 to 1987. He joined [[CITY-TV]] in 1987 as a producer of ''CityWide''. He left in 1989 to join the board of the [[World Association of Community Radio Broadcasters]].\n\nIn 1990, he joined ''[[Metro Morning]]'' on [[CBLA-FM|CBL]] as a segment producer. He subsequently joined [[CBLT-DT|CBLT]] in 1994, covering City Hall as a municipal reporter, producer, and director. Vaughan has covered [[Toronto Police Service]], [[Toronto City Hall]], [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen's Park]] and [[Canadian parliament|Parliament Hill]] in his career. He returned to the Citytv team in 2000.\n\nVaughan has written for ''[[Toronto Life]]'' magazine and the ''[[Toronto Star]]''.  Before becoming a journalist, Adam Vaughan was a cartoonist for ''[[Books in Canada]]'', ''[[Quill and Quire]]'', ''[[Canadian Forum]]'' and several other publications.\n\nAfter Marilyn Bornstein, the wife of the then mayor of Toronto [[Mel Lastman]], was caught shoplifting from an [[Eaton's]] store in Toronto, the mayor threatened to kill Vaughan If he reported on his family.<ref>Timothy Appleby, \"The mayor goes ballistic: Death threat against report has Lastman in hot water\", ''Globe and Mail'', p. A1, A3, 13 May 1999.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/1999/05/13/lastman990513.html|title=Toronto mayor threatens CBC reporter |date=November 10, 2000|work=CBC News|accessdate=August 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:Adam Vaughan headshot 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Vaughan in 2014]]\nVaughan ran in [[Trinity\u2014Spadina]] - Ward 20 in the [[2006 Toronto municipal election|2006 municipal election]]. The seat had been vacated by [[Olivia Chow]] who left the city for federal politics. He won the seat defeating [[Helen Kennedy]], Chow's executive assistant, by 2,300 votes.\n\nAfter the [[2010 Toronto mayoral election|2010 mayoral election]], Vaughan was an outspoken critic of then-[[Mayor of Toronto|Toronto Mayor]] [[Rob Ford]].\n\nAs a member of City Council Vaughan sat on the Planning and Growth Management Committee, the Toronto Arts Council, Artscape Board, the Board of Trustees for the Art Gallery of Ontario, and the Harbourfront Centre Board. Additionally he sat on the city's Heritage Board, and the city's Preservation Board.\n\nIn 2014, he ran as the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] candidate in a federal [[By-elections to the 41st Canadian Parliament|by-election]]  following [[New Democratic Party]] MP Olivia Chow's resignation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adam Vaughan wins Liberal nomination for Trinity-Spadina |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/adam-vaughan-wins-liberal-nomination-for-trinity-spadina-1.2631280 |publisher=CBC News|date=May 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Harper |first=Tim |title=Adam Vaughan to run for Liberals in federal byelection |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2014/04/17/adam_vaughan_to_run_for_liberals_in_federal_byelection.html |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=April 17, 2014}}</ref>  Vaughan resigned his city council seat on May 13, 2014, several days after the Trinity\u2014Spadina by-election was called.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adam Vaughan to Run in Trinity-Spadina By-election |url=http://www.640toronto.com/2014/05/11/adam-vaughan-to-run-in-trinity-spadina-by-election/ |publisher=AM 640 |date=May 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Adam Vaughan, on Rob Ford's legacy |url=http://www.torontolife.com/informer/toronto-politics/2014/05/14/quoted-adam-vaughan-rob-fords-legacy/ |publisher=Toronto Life |date=May 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515004639/http://www.torontolife.com/informer/toronto-politics/2014/05/14/quoted-adam-vaughan-rob-fords-legacy/ |archivedate=May 15, 2014 }}</ref> He defeated NDP candidate [[Joe Cressy]] by 6,745 votes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adam Vaughan, Arnold Chan lead Liberals to byelection wins |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2014/06/30/adam_vaughan_arnold_chan_lead_liberals_to_byelection_wins.html |first1=Susan |last1=Delacourt |first2=Donovan |last2=Vincent |first3=Robert |last3=Benzie |date=June 30, 2014 |newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref>\n\nHe served as the party's critic for urban affairs and housing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Q and A: MP Adam Vaughan on what Toronto city council taught him |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/politics/q-and-a-mp-adam-vaughan-on-what-toronto-city-council-taught-him |first=Jason |last=Fekete |date=September 17, 2014 |newspaper=Ottawa Citizen}}</ref>\n\nIn the October 2015 federal election, Vaughan ran in Spadina\u2014Fort York, essentially a reconfigured version of his old riding.  His main opponent was Chow, the person who he had replaced twice, first as a councillor at Toronto City Hall and then later as MP after Chow's resignation in early 2014 to run for the Mayor's job in Toronto.  Once the election was called, Vaughan initially trailed Chow in public opinion polls.  However, on election day, in part due to a massive surge of Liberal support in Toronto, he defeated Chow convincingly, taking 54.5% of the vote to Chow's 27.4%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Liberal candidate Adam Vaughan wins in Spadina-Fort York|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/federal-election/federal-ridings-toronto-gta/2015/10/19/liberal-candidate-adam-vaughan-wins-in-spadinafort-york.html|author= Laurie Monsebraaten|publisher=The Toronto Star|date=October 19, 2015|accessdate=October 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Elections Canada Preliminary Results|url=http://enr.elections.ca/ElectoralDistricts.aspx?lang=e|publisher=Elections Canada|accessdate=October 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn December 2, 2015, he was appointed [[Parliamentary Secretary#Canada|Parliamentary Secretary]] to the [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] for [[Minister of Intergovernmental Affairs and Youth (Canada)|Intergovernmental Affairs]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Bill Blair, Adam Vaughan among new parliamentary secretaries|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-parliamentary-secretaries-named-1.3346942|website = www.cbc.ca|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n\n===Federal elections===\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2015|Spadina\u2014Fort York|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Adam Vaughan|30,141|54.66|{{increase}}30.27|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|[[Olivia Chow]]|15,047|27.28|{{decrease}}22.36|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Sabrina Zuniga|8,673|15.73|{{decrease}}5.13|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Sharon Danley|1,137|2.06|{{decrease}}2.11|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec|CA|[[Party for Accountability, Competency and Transparency|PACT]]|Michael Nicula|91|0.17|&ndash;|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Marxist-Leninist|Nick Lin|59|0.11|&ndash;|&ndash;}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|55,148|100.0 &nbsp;|&nbsp;|$205,892.35}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|268|0.48|&ndash;}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|55,416|73.93|&ndash;}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|74,958}}\n{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Elections Canada]]<ref>[http://www.elections.ca/Scripts/vis/candidates?L=e&ED=35101&EV=41&EV_TYPE=1&PC=&PROV=ON&PROVID=35&MAPID=&QID=8&PAGEID=17&TPAGEID=&PD=&STAT_CODE_ID=-1 Elections Canada \u2013 Confirmed candidates for Spadina\u2014Fort York, 30 September 2015]</ref><ref>[http://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand/canlim&document=index&lang=e Elections Canada \u2013 Preliminary Election Expenses Limits for Candidates] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045200/http://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand%2Fcanlim&document=index&lang=e |date=2016-03-04 }}</ref>}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Canadian federal by-election, June 30, 2014/Trinity\u2014Spadina}}\n\n===Municipal elections===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''[[2010 Toronto municipal election|2010 Toronto election]], Ward 20''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''Adam Vaughan''' ||align=right| 16,486 ||align=right| 74.523% \n|-\n|Mike Yen ||align=right| 3,601 ||align=right| 16.278% \n|-\n|Dean Maher ||align=right| 1,233 ||align=right| 5.574% \n|-\n|Roman Polochansky ||align=right| 487 ||align=right| 2.201% \n|-\n|Ken Osadchuk ||align=right| 315 ||align=right| 1.424% \n|-\n!Total||align=right| 22,122 ||align=right| 100% \n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''[[2006 Toronto municipal election|2006 Toronto election]], Ward 20'''<ref>[http://www.toronto.ca/vote2006/results/officialdeclaration.pdf City Clerk's Official Declaration 2006] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607042449/http://www.toronto.ca/vote2006/results/officialdeclaration.pdf |date=2011-06-07 }}</ref>  \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''Adam Vaughan''' ||align=right|7,834||align=right|51.7\n|-\n|[[Helen Kennedy]] ||align=right|5,334||align=right|35.2\n|-\n| [[Desmond Cole]] ||align=right|750||align=right|4.9\n|-\n|Chris Ouellette ||align=right|375||align=right|2.5\n|-\n|Joseph Tuan ||align=right|359||align=right|2.4\n|-\n|Devendra Sharma ||align=right|231||align=right|1.5\n|-\n|Douglas Lowry ||align=right|193||align=right|1.3\n|-\n|Carmin Priolo ||align=right|91||align=right|0.6\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Canadian Parliament links|ID=18280}}\n*{{official website|http://adamvaughan.liberal.ca/}}\n\n{{Current Members of the Canadian House of Commons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vaughan, Adam}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Australian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Ryerson University alumni]]\n[[Category:Toronto city councillors]]\n[[Category:Writers from Toronto]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| image            = Adam Vaughan - 2017 Homelessness Summit (32445688516) (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Vaughan in 2017\n| honorific-suffix ={{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP|size=100%}}\n| office1           = [[Parliamentary Secretary]] to the [[Minister of Families, Children and Social Development]] (Housing)\n| minister1         = [[Jean-Yves Duclos]]\n| term_start1       = January 30, 2017\n| term_end1         = \n| predecessor1      = [[Terry Duguid]]\n| successor1        =\n\n| office2           = [[Parliamentary Secretary]] to the [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] (Intergovernmental Affairs)\n| minister2         = [[Justin Trudeau]]\n| term_start2       = December 2, 2015\n| term_end2         = January 27, 2017\n| predecessor2      = [[Paul Calandra]]\n| successor2        = [[Peter Schiefke]]\n\n| riding3            = [[Spadina-Fort York]]<br /><small>[[Trinity\u2014Spadina]] (2014-2015)</small>\n| parliament3        = Canadian\n| term_start3        = June 30, 2014\n| term_end3          =\n| predecessor3       = [[Olivia Chow]]\n| successor3         =\n| office4          = [[Toronto City Councillor]] for [[Trinity-Spadina|(Ward 20) Trinity-Spadina]]\n| term_start4      = December 1, 2006\n| term_end4        = May 13, 2014\n| predecessor4     = [[Martin Silva]]\n| successor4       = [[Ceta Ramkhalawansingh]]\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1961|7|3}}\n| birth_place      = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]. Canada\n| nationality      = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| occupation       = Journalist\n}}\n'''Adam Vaughan''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP}} (born July 3, 1961) is a politician in [[Ontario]], Canada. He is a [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] member of the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] in the federal government who was elected in a [[By-elections to the 41st Canadian Parliament|by-election]] on June 30, 2014. He is currently the MP for [[Spadina\u2014Fort York]], and the [[Parliamentary Secretary]] to the  [[Minister of Families, Children and Social Development]] (Housing and Urban Affairs). From 2006 to 2014 he was a Toronto city councillor who represented Ward 20 [[Trinity\u2014Spadina]]. Prior to his career in politics he was a radio and TV journalist.\n\n==Background==\nHe is married to Nicole Anatol and he has a son (Salvador) and a daughter (Mimi) from previous relationships. Mimi's mother is journalist [[Suhana Meharchand]].<ref name=kuitenbrouwer>Kuitenbrouwer, P. May 18, 2006. [http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/toronto/story.html?id=8728595a-2455-45f4-a13d-7641487ff9f3 \"No longer a journalist, now candidate for council\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060830230121/http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/toronto/story.html?id=8728595a-2455-45f4-a13d-7641487ff9f3 |date=August 30, 2006 }}. ''[[National Post]]''. Retrieved June 1, 2007.</ref> His father, [[Colin Vaughan]], was a noted architect, television journalist and former city councillor, who preceded Adam as [[City (TV network)|Citytv's]] political reporter until his death in 2000.\n\n==Journalism==\nAdam Vaughan worked at [[Ryerson University]] radio station [[CKLN-FM|CKLN]] from 1982 to 1987, and was manager of the station from 1985 to 1987. He joined [[CITY-TV]] in 1987 as a producer of ''CityWide''. He left in 1989 to join the board of the [[World Association of Community Radio Broadcasters]].\n\nIn 1990, he joined ''[[Metro Morning]]'' on [[CBLA-FM|CBL]] as a segment producer. He subsequently joined [[CBLT-DT|CBLT]] in 1994, covering City Hall as a municipal reporter, producer, and director. Vaughan has covered [[Toronto Police Service]], [[Toronto City Hall]], [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen's Park]] and [[Canadian parliament|Parliament Hill]] in his career. He returned to the Citytv team in 2000.\n\nVaughan has written for ''[[Toronto Life]]'' magazine and the ''[[Toronto Star]]''.  Before becoming a journalist, Adam Vaughan was a cartoonist for ''[[Books in Canada]]'', ''[[Quill and Quire]]'', ''[[Canadian Forum]]'' and several other publications.\n\nAfter Marilyn Bornstein, the wife of the then mayor of Toronto [[Mel Lastman]], was caught shoplifting from an [[Eaton's]] store in Toronto, the mayor threatened to kill Vaughan If he reported on his family.<ref>Timothy Appleby, \"The mayor goes ballistic: Death threat against report has Lastman in hot water\", ''Globe and Mail'', p. A1, A3, 13 May 1999.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/1999/05/13/lastman990513.html|title=Toronto mayor threatens CBC reporter |date=November 10, 2000|work=CBC News|accessdate=August 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:Adam Vaughan headshot 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Vaughan in 2014]]\nVaughan ran in [[Trinity\u2014Spadina]] - Ward 20 in the [[2006 Toronto municipal election|2006 municipal election]]. The seat had been vacated by [[Olivia Chow]] who left the city for federal politics. He won the seat defeating [[Helen Kennedy]], Chow's executive assistant, by 2,300 votes.\n\nAfter the [[2010 Toronto mayoral election|2010 mayoral election]], Vaughan was an outspoken critic of then-[[Mayor of Toronto|Toronto Mayor]] [[Rob Ford]].\n\nAs a member of City Council Vaughan sat on the Planning and Growth Management Committee, the Toronto Arts Council, Artscape Board, the Board of Trustees for the Art Gallery of Ontario, and the Harbourfront Centre Board. Additionally he sat on the city's Heritage Board, and the city's Preservation Board.\n\nIn 2014, he ran as the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] candidate in a federal [[By-elections to the 41st Canadian Parliament|by-election]]  following [[New Democratic Party]] MP Olivia Chow's resignation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adam Vaughan wins Liberal nomination for Trinity-Spadina |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/adam-vaughan-wins-liberal-nomination-for-trinity-spadina-1.2631280 |publisher=CBC News|date=May 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Harper |first=Tim |title=Adam Vaughan to run for Liberals in federal byelection |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2014/04/17/adam_vaughan_to_run_for_liberals_in_federal_byelection.html |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=April 17, 2014}}</ref>  Vaughan resigned his city council seat on May 13, 2014, several days after the Trinity\u2014Spadina by-election was called.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adam Vaughan to Run in Trinity-Spadina By-election |url=http://www.640toronto.com/2014/05/11/adam-vaughan-to-run-in-trinity-spadina-by-election/ |publisher=AM 640 |date=May 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Adam Vaughan, on Rob Ford's legacy |url=http://www.torontolife.com/informer/toronto-politics/2014/05/14/quoted-adam-vaughan-rob-fords-legacy/ |publisher=Toronto Life |date=May 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515004639/http://www.torontolife.com/informer/toronto-politics/2014/05/14/quoted-adam-vaughan-rob-fords-legacy/ |archivedate=May 15, 2014 }}</ref> He defeated NDP candidate [[Joe Cressy]] by 6,745 votes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adam Vaughan, Arnold Chan lead Liberals to byelection wins |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2014/06/30/adam_vaughan_arnold_chan_lead_liberals_to_byelection_wins.html |first1=Susan |last1=Delacourt |first2=Donovan |last2=Vincent |first3=Robert |last3=Benzie |date=June 30, 2014 |newspaper=Toronto Star}}</ref>\n\nHe served as the party's critic for urban affairs and housing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Q and A: MP Adam Vaughan on what Toronto city council taught him |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/politics/q-and-a-mp-adam-vaughan-on-what-toronto-city-council-taught-him |first=Jason |last=Fekete |date=September 17, 2014 |newspaper=Ottawa Citizen}}</ref>\n\nIn the October 2015 federal election, Vaughan ran in Spadina\u2014Fort York, essentially a reconfigured version of his old riding.  His main opponent was Chow, the person who he had replaced twice, first as a councillor at Toronto City Hall and then later as MP after Chow's resignation in early 2014 to run for the Mayor's job in Toronto.  Once the election was called, Vaughan initially trailed Chow in public opinion polls.  However, on election day, in part due to a massive surge of Liberal support in Toronto, he defeated Chow convincingly, taking 54.5% of the vote to Chow's 27.4%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Liberal candidate Adam Vaughan wins in Spadina-Fort York|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/federal-election/federal-ridings-toronto-gta/2015/10/19/liberal-candidate-adam-vaughan-wins-in-spadinafort-york.html|author= Laurie Monsebraaten|publisher=The Toronto Star|date=October 19, 2015|accessdate=October 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Elections Canada Preliminary Results|url=http://enr.elections.ca/ElectoralDistricts.aspx?lang=e|publisher=Elections Canada|accessdate=October 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn December 2, 2015, he was appointed [[Parliamentary Secretary#Canada|Parliamentary Secretary]] to the [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] for [[Minister of Intergovernmental Affairs and Youth (Canada)|Intergovernmental Affairs]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Bill Blair, Adam Vaughan among new parliamentary secretaries|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-parliamentary-secretaries-named-1.3346942|website = www.cbc.ca|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n\n===Federal elections===\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2015|Spadina\u2014Fort York|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Adam Vaughan|30,141|54.66|{{increase}}30.27|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|[[Olivia Chow]]|15,047|27.28|{{decrease}}22.36|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Sabrina Zuniga|8,673|15.73|{{decrease}}5.13|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Sharon Danley|1,137|2.06|{{decrease}}2.11|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec|CA|[[Party for Accountability, Competency and Transparency|PACT]]|Michael Nicula|91|0.17|&ndash;|&ndash;}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Marxist-Leninist|Nick Lin|59|0.11|&ndash;|&ndash;}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|55,148|100.0 &nbsp;|&nbsp;|$205,892.35}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|268|0.48|&ndash;}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|55,416|73.93|&ndash;}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|74,958}}\n{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Elections Canada]]<ref>[http://www.elections.ca/Scripts/vis/candidates?L=e&ED=35101&EV=41&EV_TYPE=1&PC=&PROV=ON&PROVID=35&MAPID=&QID=8&PAGEID=17&TPAGEID=&PD=&STAT_CODE_ID=-1 Elections Canada \u2013 Confirmed candidates for Spadina\u2014Fort York, 30 September 2015]</ref><ref>[http://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand/canlim&document=index&lang=e Elections Canada \u2013 Preliminary Election Expenses Limits for Candidates] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045200/http://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand%2Fcanlim&document=index&lang=e |date=2016-03-04 }}</ref>}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Canadian federal by-election, June 30, 2014/Trinity\u2014Spadina}}\n\n===Municipal elections===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''[[2010 Toronto municipal election|2010 Toronto election]], Ward 20''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''Adam Vaughan''' ||align=right| 16,486 ||align=right| 74.523% \n|-\n|Mike Yen ||align=right| 3,601 ||align=right| 16.278% \n|-\n|Dean Maher ||align=right| 1,233 ||align=right| 5.574% \n|-\n|Roman Polochansky ||align=right| 487 ||align=right| 2.201% \n|-\n|Ken Osadchuk ||align=right| 315 ||align=right| 1.424% \n|-\n!Total||align=right| 22,122 ||align=right| 100% \n|}\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"7\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''[[2006 Toronto municipal election|2006 Toronto election]], Ward 20'''<ref>[http://www.toronto.ca/vote2006/results/officialdeclaration.pdf City Clerk's Official Declaration 2006] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607042449/http://www.toronto.ca/vote2006/results/officialdeclaration.pdf |date=2011-06-07 }}</ref>  \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''Adam Vaughan''' ||align=right|7,834||align=right|51.7\n|-\n|[[Helen Kennedy]] ||align=right|5,334||align=right|35.2\n|-\n| [[Desmond Cole]] ||align=right|750||align=right|4.9\n|-\n|Chris Ouellette ||align=right|375||align=right|2.5\n|-\n|Joseph Tuan ||align=right|359||align=right