ices and Postmasters \n |url=http://www.collectionscanada.ca/archivianet/post-offices/001001-100.01-e.php \n |accessdate=29 September 2013 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061006045957/http://www.collectionscanada.ca/archivianet/post-offices/001001-100.01-e.php \n |archivedate=October 6, 2006 \n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web\n |last=Government of Saskatchewan \n |first=MRD Home \n |title=Municipal Directory System (City of Humboldt) \n |url=http://www.mds.gov.sk.ca/apps/Pub/MDS/welcome.aspx \n |accessdate=29 September 2013 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115125115/http://www.mds.gov.sk.ca/apps/Pub/MDS/welcome.aspx \n |archivedate=January 15, 2016 \n}}</ref>\n|city_logo              =\n|citylogo_size          =\n|image_dot_map          =\n|dot_mapsize            =\n|dot_map_caption        =\n|dot_x =  \n|dot_y =\n|leader_title3          = {{nowrap|[[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]], [[Humboldt-Watrous]]}}\n|leader_name3           = [[Donna Harpauer]] ([[Saskatchewan Party|SKP]])\n|leader_title4          = [[Member of Parliament|MP]], [[Carlton Trail\u2014Eagle Creek]]\n|leader_name4           = [[Kelly Block]] ([[Conservative Party of Canada|CPC]])\n|timezone               = [[North American Central Time Zone|CST]]\n|utc_offset             = -6\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|blank_name             = [[List of Saskatchewan provincial highways|Highways]]\n|blank_info             = {{jct|state=SK|Hwy|5|Hwy|20}}\n|blank1_name            = [[Rail transport in Canada|Railways]]\n|blank1_info            = [[Canadian National Railway|Canadian National]]\n}}\n\n'''Humboldt''' is a city in the province of [[Saskatchewan]], Canada. It is located 113&nbsp;km east of [[Saskatoon]] at the junction of [[Saskatchewan Highway 5|Highway 5]] and [[Saskatchewan Highway 20|Highway 20]]. The city is surrounded by the [[Humboldt No. 370, Saskatchewan|Rural Municipality of Humboldt No. 370]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Humboldt Telegraph Station2.JPG|thumb|left|Humboldt Telegraph Station (circa 1885)]]\n[[File:Humboldt Post Office.jpg|thumb|left|[[Humboldt Post Office]], which is now home of the Humboldt & District Museum]]\nNamed after German explorer [[Alexander von Humboldt]], Humboldt began as a telegraph station located on the [[Carlton Trail]], a wagon route used in the early days of [[Canadian Prairies|Western Canada]] as a route from [[Fort Garry]] (Winnipeg) to [[Fort Edmonton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humboldtmuseum.ca/content/humboldt-history|title=Humboldt History|author=Humboldt Museum|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref> The name \"Humboldt\" was approved in 1875 for a site in the North West Territories along the Canadian Pacific Telegraph Line at which a repair station was built (8&nbsp;km south-west of the present city site).  Built in 1878, the Humboldt Telegraph Station<ref>[http://www.museevirtuel-virtualmuseum.ca/Search.do?ex=on&R=VE_1318&lang=en A Line Through the Wilderness]</ref> played an integral part in communications for the developing West.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.humboldt.ca/default.aspx?page=31 |title= Humboldt History |publisher= City of Humboldt |accessdate= 2009-10-02}}</ref>\n\nWith the [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis]] uprising led by [[Louis Riel]] taking place at [[Batoche, Saskatchewan|Batoche]] just 100&nbsp;km northwest, Humboldt became the only communication link between Prime Minister [[John A. Macdonald]] and his forces in the West, thus a site of strategic significance. General [[Frederick Middleton]] arrived in April 1885 with 950 soldiers, established a garrison at the station, and used it as his base for scouting operations. At that time, the Humboldt station was crucial, since the telegraph line further west was periodically cut \u2013 so Humboldt was the last secure link to the East.<ref>{{Cite web\n  |work = University of Regina\n  | title = District of Saskatchewan Map 1885\n  | url =http://esask.uregina.ca/management/app/assets/img/enc2/PDF/51C276D2-1560-95DA-430F6CC3E32921701.pdf\n  | accessdate =2013-12-01}}</ref>\n\nOn May 1, 1885, Humboldt became the site of a large supply depot under Maj. Lt.-Colonel G. T. Denison of the Governor Generals' Body Guard. A combined force of approximately 460 men built an elaborate series of entrenchments, converting the station into a fortified military encampment to protect the supplies.  The troops left Humboldt in July 1885.  The area was also the site of the first stagecoach robbery in Western Canada.<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = The Legacy of St. Peter's Colony(P.12)\n |url         = http://www.ourroots.ca/e/page.aspx?id=1072358\n |accessdate  = 2013-01-06\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140529085939/http://www.ourroots.ca/e/page.aspx?id=1072358\n |archivedate = 2014-05-29\n}}</ref> Parts of the Carlton Trail in the form of wagon tracks/ruts still exist in the Humboldt area.\n\nHumboldt in its beginnings was primarily [[Germans|German]] [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Saskatoon|Catholic]]. It became the largest settlement in the [[St. Peter's Abbey, Saskatchewan|Territorial Abbey of Saint Peter-Muenster]] also called St. Peter's Colony<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = St. Peter's Colony Map\n |url         = http://www.ourroots.ca/e/page.aspx?id=1072358\n |accessdate  = 2013-01-06\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140529085939/http://www.ourroots.ca/e/page.aspx?id=1072358\n |archivedate = 2014-05-29\n}}</ref> established by [[Benedictine]] monks from St John's Abbey in [[Collegeville, Minnesota|Collegeville]], [[Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Territorial Abbey of Saint Peter-Muenster\n| url =http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/ds005.html\n| date = \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref> Immigration to the area from both the [[Northern Plains]] states of the US and Germany was promoted by the German American Land Company. Many immigrants from the [[German Empire]] settled in areas in and around Humboldt such as [[Muenster, Saskatchewan|Muenster]], [[Fulda, Saskatchewan|Fulda]], [[Pilger, Saskatchewan|Pilger]], [[St. Gregor, Saskatchewan|St Gregor]] and [[Englefeld, Saskatchewan|Englefeld]]. Immigrants from the [[Russian Empire]] who were [[History of Germans in Russia, Ukraine and the Soviet Union|ethnic Germans]] settled in the area west of Humboldt and south of the hamlet of [[Carmel, Saskatchewan|Carmel]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://esask.uregina.ca/entry/german_settlements.html\n|title = Encyclopedia of Saskatchewan (GERMAN SETTLEMENTS)\n|work = Encyclopedia of Saskatchewan\n|publisher = Canadian Plains Research Center, [[University of Regina]]\n|year = 2006\n|accessdate = 2013-09-18\n|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170505210802/http://esask.uregina.ca/entry/german_settlements.html\n|archive-date = 2017-05-05\n|url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nAfter being established as a community, Humboldt became an important location in Saskatchewan previously known as the \"Heart of the Sure Crop District\" for its reliable growing weather, which led the town to become a centre for farming equipment and supply businesses.\n\n===Humboldt Broncos bus crash===\n{{main|Humboldt Broncos bus crash}}\nOn April 6, 2018, the [[Humboldt Broncos]] junior hockey team was involved in a [[Humboldt Broncos bus crash|serious bus crash]].<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/nipawin-humboldt-bus-crash-1.4609835</ref> The bus was carrying the team to a playoff game in [[Nipawin, Saskatchewan]] when it collided with a tractor trailer loaded with peat moss at an intersection known as Armley Corner, near Nipawin. Sixteen of the 30 people on board the bus died \u2014 the driver, the general manager/head coach, the assistant coach, a radio commentator, a volunteer, the club's female trainer, and 10 players between the ages of 16 and 21.<ref>http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/23056409/bus-carrying-humboldt-broncos-saskatchewan-junior-hockey-league-involved-fatal-collision</ref>  Fourteen players were injured, several of them seriously.  News of the crash received significant national and international media coverage, and numerous dignitaries and politicians sent their condolences to the team and city.  Two days after the crash, a vigil was held at the Elgar Petersen Arena in Humboldt, which was attended by over 5,000 people and televised nationally.  Attendees included Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]], the [[Premier of Saskatchewan]], and popular Canadian sports personalities [[Don Cherry]] and [[Ron MacLean]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Quenneville|first1=Guy|title='We will get through this': Hundreds honour Humboldt Broncos at vigil on home ice|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/trudeau-premier-vigil-mourning-humboldt-broncos-bus-crash-1.4610591|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=April 8, 2018|date=April 8, 2018}}</ref>  Humboldt Mayor Rob Muench called the tragedy a \"truly dark moment\" for the city.<ref>[https://www.msn.com/en-ca/news/videos/this-is-truly-a-dark-moment-for-our-city-humboldt-mayor-on-bus-crash/vi-AAvBhSg \\ 'This is truly a dark moment for our city': Humboldt mayor on bus crash]</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nHumboldt experiences a [[humid continental climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Dfb'')<ref name=climateclassification>{{cite web|title=Climate Regions |url=http://ftp2.cits.rncan.gc.ca/pub/geott/atlas/archives/english/3rdedition/environment/climate/030.jpg |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909022911/http://ftp2.cits.rncan.gc.ca/pub/geott/atlas/archives/english/3rdedition/environment/climate/030.jpg |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 September 2015 |website=FTP Home - Natural Resources Canada Archives |publisher=Natural Resources Canada |accessdate=9 April 2016 |format=Image (JPE) FTP }}</ref> featuring long, cold winters and brief, warm summers. The region falls into the USDA [[Hardiness zone|Plant Hardiness Zone]] 3a.<ref name=\"Canadian Plant Hardiness Zones\">{{cite web|title=Plant Hardiness Zone by Municipality|url=http://www.planthardiness.gc.ca/?m=22&lang=en&prov=Alberta&val=E|website=Natural Resources Canada|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> It is a great distance from any large bodies of water, and thus lacks any moderating influences on its climate. The latitudinal difference of Saskatchewan can typically explain a 6\u20138&nbsp;\u00b0C difference mean in annual temperatures across the province.\n\nThe highest temperature ever recorded in Humboldt was {{convert|41.1|C|0}} on 19 July 1941.<ref name=\"July 1941\">[[Environment Canada]]\n[http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=%7C&dlyRange=1879-12-01%7C1974-02-28&mlyRange=1880-01-01%7C1974-12-01&StationID=2922&Prov=SK&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnName&optLimit=yearRange&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&selRowPerPage=25&Line=0&searchMethod=contains&txtStationName=humboldt&timeframe=2&Year=1941&Month=7], accessed 11 July 2016</ref> The coldest temperature ever recorded was {{convert|-50.6|C|0}} on 12 January 1916.<ref name=\"January 1916\">[[Environment Canada]]\n[http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=%7C&dlyRange=1879-12-01%7C1974-02-28&mlyRange=1880-01-01%7C1974-12-01&StationID=2922&Prov=SK&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnName&optLimit=yearRange&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&selRowPerPage=25&Line=0&searchMethod=contains&txtStationName=humboldt&timeframe=2&Year=1916&Month=1]</ref>\n\n{{Weather box|location = Humboldt\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 6.0\n|Feb record high C = 15.0\n|Mar record high C = 20.6\n|Apr record high C = 32.2\n|May record high C = 36.0\n|Jun record high C = 39.0\n|Jul record high C = 41.1\n|Aug record high C = 38.3\n|Sep record high C = 34.4\n|Oct record high C = 31.1\n|Nov record high C = 21.1\n|Dec record high C = 10.0\n|year record high C = 41.1\n|Jan 