 of people in the city and surrounding district.\n\n==Attractions==\n{{see also|List of historic places in Saskatchewan}}\nHumboldt has a number of heritage buildings listed on the Canadian Register of Historic Places. They include the Canadian National Railways (Canadian Northern Railway) Station (built in 1905),<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Canadian National Railways (Canadian Northern Railway) Station\n| url =http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=4560&pid=0 \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref> a Post Office (built in 1911\u20131912),<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Post Office\n| url =http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=2880&pid=0 \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref> the Humboldt Provincial Court House (built in 1914\u20131920).<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Provincial Court House\n| url =http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=2871&pid=0| date =  \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref> and the Humboldt Water Tower (built in 1914) has been renovated with a spiral staircase and a circular observation platform on top.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Water Tower\n| url =http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=2787&pid=0| date =  \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref>\n\nThe Humboldt Post Office is a National Historic Site of Canada (built in 1911\u20131912). It houses the [http://www.humboldtmuseum.ca/ Humboldt and District Museum and Gallery].<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Humboldt Post Office National Historic Site of Canada\n| url =http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=11807&pid=0 \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref> Across the street is the Humboldt and District Art Gallery in the old Merchant Bank Building.\n\n[[Marysburg Assumption Church]] is located 16&nbsp;km (10 miles) north of Humboldt.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Marysburg Assumption Church \n| url =http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=8942&pid=0| date =  \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref>\n[[Mount Carmel Shrine (Saskatchewan)|Mount Carmel Shrine]] is located 23&nbsp;km (14 miles) west and [[St. Peter's Abbey, Saskatchewan|St. Peter's Abbey]] and St. Peter's Cathedral are 10&nbsp;km (6 miles) east of the city in Muenster.\n\nThe Humboldt Murals located in the town centre depict historic scenes.\n\n===Festivals===\n*The Summer Sizzler is held in late-June of each year. The event features a midway, demolition derby, cabaret, slo-pitch tournament, tractor pull, Sizzler Strut Marathon and live on-stage entertainment. On the opening day, there is a parade through downtown and a pancake breakfast at Centennial Park.\n*Canada Day celebrations occur every year on July 1 concluding with fireworks at Water Ridge Park.\n*The Humboldt StreetFest is held in mid-August and is organized by the Humboldt Downtown Business Improvement District.\n\n==Sports and recreation==\n\nHumboldt is home to over 30 acres of parks and open spaces as well as a growing pedestrian trails and pathways system.\nThere are eleven parks around the city, including: A.E. Kilcher Park, Bill Brecht Memorial Park, Carl Schenn Recreational Park, Centennial Park, Civic Park, Glenn Hall Park, Peace Park, St. Augustine School Grounds, St. Dominic School Grounds, Water Ridge Park, St. Elizabeth Park and Wilf Chamney Park.\n\nSituated {{convert|4|mi|km}} west of Humboldt along [[Saskatchewan Highway 5|Highway 5]] and two miles (3&nbsp;km) south is the Kloppenburg Wildlife Refuge. It consists of {{convert|160|acre|km2}} which have never been cultivated.\n\nThe Uniplex is Humboldt's recreational facility featuring a curling rink, an indoor aquatic center, a fitness center and a convention center.  The Elgar Petersen Arena, part of the Uniplex, is a 1,900-seat arena, home to the [[Humboldt Broncos]] of the [[Saskatchewan Junior Hockey League]], two-time [[Royal Bank Cup|National Champions]] and 10-time SJHL Champions, as well as Humboldt's minor hockey teams and club skating club.  Also on the Uniplex grounds is Centennial Park with ball diamonds, a skateboard park and a soccer/football field.\n\nAn 18-hole golf course is located next to Water Ridge Park, which includes walking trails, a spray park and gazebo and the Humboldt Historical Park, mini golf and campground.\n\nSt. Elizabeth Park features Humboldt's 9 hole disc golf course.\n\n==Churches==\nHumboldt has ten churches: Humboldt Alliance Church, St. John's Lutheran, St. Andrew's Anglican Church, St. Augustine Catholic Church, Living Word Ministries, All Saints Ukrainian Catholic Church, Humboldt Bible Church, Westminster United Church of Canada, First Baptist Church and Kingdom Hall of Jehovah's Witnesses.<ref name=\"city\"/>\n\n==Education==\n{{Infobox school\n| name                   = Humboldt Collegiate Institute\n| image                  = \n| image_size             = 250px\n| caption                = \n| motto                  = \n| address                = 509 8th Avenue\n| city                   = Humboldt\n| province               = [[Saskatchewan]]\n| country                = [[Canada]]\n| postalcode             = S0K 2A1\n| coordinates            = \n| opened                 = <!--{{Start date|YYYY}}-->\n| schoolboard            = [[Horizon School Division No. 205]]<br />[[Greater Saskatoon Catholic Schools]]\n| system                 = Public/[[Separate school|Separate]]\n| type                   = Secondary\n| language               = English\n| grades                 = Grade 9 to grade 12\n| principal              = Cory Popoff\n| principal_label2       = Vice principal\n| principal2             = David Millette\n| principal_label3       = Vice principal\n| principal3             = Shaun Gardiner\n| enrollment             = 390<ref name=\"enrollment\">{{Citation|title=Active List of Saskatchewan Schools/Programs|url=http://publications.gov.sk.ca/documents/11/104735-2017-18%20Active%20List%20of%20School%20Division%20Schools.pdf|accessdate=2018-02-10}}</ref>\n| enrollment_as_of       = 2017\n| staff                  = <!-- Count -->\n| team_name              = \n| colours                = \n| website                = [http://hci.hzsd.ca/ Humboldt Collegiate Institute]\n}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                   = Humboldt Public School\n| image                  = \n| image_size             = 250px\n| caption                = \n| motto                  = \n| address                = 509 8th Avenue\n| city                   = Humboldt\n| province               = [[Saskatchewan]]\n| country                = [[Canada]]\n| postalcode             = S0K 2A1\n| coordinates            = \n| opened                 = <!--{{Start date|YYYY}}-->\n| schoolboard            = [[Horizon School Division No. 205]]\n| system                 = Public\n| type                   = Elementary\n| language               = English\n| grades                 = Pre-kindergarten to grade 8\n| principal              = Clayton Parobec\n| principal_label2       = Vice principal\n| principal2             = Darlene Popoff\n| enrollment             = 272<ref name=\"enrollment\"/>\n| enrollment_as_of       = 2017\n| staff                  = <!-- Count -->\n| team_name              = \n| colours                = \n| website                = [http://humboldtpublicschool.hzsd.ca/ Humboldt Public School]\n}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                   = St. Augustine School\n| image                  = \n| image_size             = 250px\n| caption                = \n| motto                  = \n| address                = 1103 8th Avenue\n| city                   = Humboldt\n| province               = [[Saskatchewan]]\n| country                = [[Canada]]\n| postalcode             = S0K 2A1\n| coordinates            = \n| opened                 = {{Start date|1907}}<ref name=\"hauhistory\">{{cite book\n| author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n| title = Celebrating a Century of Faith and Learning - A History of Saskatoon's Catholic Schools\n| year = 2015\n| publisher = Greater Saskatoon Catholic Schools\n| page = 196\n| isbn =978-0-9947443-0-2}}</ref>\n| schoolboard            = [[Greater Saskatoon Catholic Schools]]\n| religion               = [[Catholicism|Catholic]]\n| system                 = [[Separate school|Separate]]\n| type                   = Elementary\n| language               = English\n| grades                 = Kindergarten to grade 8\n| principal              = Cal Theisen\n| principal_label2       = Vice principal\n| principal2             = Cathy Korte-Monz\n| enrollment             = 323<ref name=\"enrollment\" />\n| enrollment_as_of       = 2017\n| staff                  = <!-- Count -->\n| team_name              = \n| colours                = \n| website                = [http://www.gscs.ca/hau St. Augustine School]\n}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                   = St. Dominic School\n| image                  = \n| image_size             = 250px\n| caption                = \n| motto                  = \n| address                = 706 2nd Avenue South\n| city                   = Humboldt\n| province               = [[Saskatchewan]]\n| country                = [[Canada]]\n| postalcode             = S0K 2A1\n| coordinates            = \n| opened                 = {{Start date|1959}}<ref name=\"hdohistory\">{{cite book\n| author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n| title = Celebrating a Century of Faith and Learning - A History of Saskatoon's Catholic Schools\n| year = 2015\n| publisher = Greater Saskatoon Catholic Schools\n| page = 198\n| isbn =978-0-9947443-0-2}}</ref>\n| schoolboard            = [[Greater Saskatoon Catholic Schools]]\n| religion               = [[Catholicism|Catholic]]\n| system                 = [[Separate school|Separate]]\n| type                   = Elementary\n| language               = English\n| grades                 = Kindergarten to grade 8\n| principal              = Chad Knaus\n| principal_label2       = Vice principal\n| principal2             = Celese LeRay-Leicht\n| enrollment             = 221<ref name=\"enrollment\" />\n| enrollment_as_of       = 2017\n| staff                  = <!-- Count -->\n| team_name              = \n| colours                = \n| website                = [http://www.gscs.ca/hdo St. Dominic School]\n}}\nHumboldt has three elementary schools: two Catholic (St. Augustine and St. Dominic) and one public (Humboldt Public School).\n\nIt has one public high school, Humboldt Collegiate Institute. It is co-managed by [[Horizon School Division No. 205]] and [[Greater Saskatoon Catholic Schools]].<ref>{{Citation|title=HCI Joint Operations Committee|url=http://hci.hzsd.ca/01636CEE-011EDEB3?object=/Web%20Pages/JOC&ConfPosition=1&infobar=no|accessdate=2015-06-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304234059/http://hci.hzsd.ca/01636CEE-011EDEB3?object=%2FWeb%20Pages%2FJOC&ConfPosition=1&infobar=no|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The [https://web.archive.org/web/20130704031126/http://hci.hzsd.ca/ Humboldt Collegiate Institute] has senior and junior [[volleyball]] teams (boys' and girls'), senior and junior [[basketball]] teams (boys' and girls'), [[soccer]] (boys' and girls'), [[badminton]], [[golf]], [[Cross country running|cross-country]], [[track & field]] and a nine-man [[Canadian football|football]] program known as HCI Mohawks. The Mohawks won provincial championships in 1975, 1996, 1997, 2008 and 2010.\n\nCarlton Trail Regional College has its headquarters in Humboldt.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\nThe city is served by [[Saskatchewan Highway 5|Highway 5]] and [[Saskatchewan Highway 20|Highway 20]].\n\n[[Humboldt Airport]], (TC LID: CJU4), is located 1 nautical mile (1.9&nbsp;km; 1.2&nbsp;mi) south of the city.\n\nHumboldt is serviced by CN Rail and is home to a number of rail workers.\n\n===Health care===\nHumboldt District Health Complex is home to the Humboldt Hospital and Community Health Services. Humboldt has two medical clinics and four pharmacies in addition to local dental, chiropractic, home care, optometry, physiotherapy as well as health and wellness services.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Saskatoon Health Region (Humboldt District Health Complex)\n| url =https://www.saskatoonhealthregion.ca/locations_services/locations/Pages/Hospitals/Humboldt-District-Health-Complex.aspx\n| accessdate =2014-07-27}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n\n===Humboldt City Council===\nThe Humboldt City Council is the municipal governing body for the city. The council consists of the [[mayor]] and six [[councillor]]s. The current council sits between 2016 and 2020. The last civic election was held on October 26, 2016. Historically, the mayor and councillors were elected to three-year terms; however, the terms have increased to four years. Rob Muench was elected for his first term as Mayor in the 2016 election, he had previously been on City Council for 10 years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.humboldt.ca/files/2012_Humboldt%20Official%20Election%20Results.pdf |title=humboldt.ca |access-date=2014-02-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222175310/http://www.humboldt.ca/files/2012_Humboldt%20Official%20Election%20Results.pdf |archive-date=2014-02-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''2016 Election Results (Councillors)''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''Roger Nordick'''||align=right| '''1,255''' ||align=right| \n|-\n|'''Sandy Weiland''' ||align=right| '''1,233''' ||align=right|  \n|-\n|'''Larry Jorgenson''' ||align=right| '''1,161''' ||align=right| \n|-\n|'''Michael Behiel''' ||align=right| '''1,112''' ||align=right| \n|-\n|'''Lorne Pratchler'''||align=right| '''1,034''' ||align=right| \n|-\n|'''Owen Hopfner'''||align=right| '''914''' ||align=right| \n|-\n|Terry Schatz||align=right| 896 ||align=right| \n|-\n|Amanda Klitch ||align=right| 869 ||align=right| \n|-\n|Justin Arndt||align=right| 637 ||align=right|  \n|-\n|Francis Kunz ||align=right| 443 ||align=right| \n|-\n|Sandor Demeter ||align=right| 146 ||align=right|  \n|-\n\n|}\n\n===Legislative Assembly of Saskatchewan===\n\nThe City of Humboldt is the largest centre in the provincial electoral district of [[Humboldt-Watrous]]. [[Donna Harpauer]] of the [[Saskatchewan Party]] is the current [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]] for the riding.\n\n===Member of Parliament===\n\nThe City of Humboldt is currently within the federal electoral district of [[Carlton Trail\u2014Eagle Creek]] which is represented by [[Kelly Block]] of the [[Conservative Party of Canada]].\n\n== Notable people ==\nNotable people who were born, grew up in or established their fame in Humboldt:\n\n* [[Kelly Bates]], former CFL [[Guard (Canadian football)|guard]], former head coach with the [[Simon Fraser Clan]] (2015-2017), and current assistant coach with the Edmonton Eskimos \n* [[Al Duerr]], former mayor of [[Calgary]], Alberta\n* Andrew Ford, Disney animator and Oscar winner<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bridges|first1=Alicia|title=A puppeteer of pixels: Sask. animator works on Disney blockbusters|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/saskatchewan-animator-andrew-ford-disney-1.3936095|accessdate=10 May 2017|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Jillian Gallays]], wrestler\n* [[Glenn Hall]], former professional [[ice hockey]] [[goaltender]]. [[Stanley Cup]] champion and [[Hockey Hall of Fame]] inductee\n* [[Lylian Klimek]], sculptor\n* [[Ross Lonsberry]], professional [[ice hockey]] player, two-time Stanley Cup champion with the [[Philadelphia Flyers]]\n* [[Otto Lang]], Rhodes Scholar, law school dean, Federal Cabinet Minister, and executive\n* [[Brad Lauer]], former [[NHL]] [[forward (ice hockey)|forward]] and current assistant coach with the [[Anaheim Ducks]]\n* [[Kyle McLaren]], former [[NHL]]  [[defenceman (ice hockey)|defenceman]]\n* [[Brendan Witt]], former [[NHL]] [[defenceman (ice hockey)|defenceman]]\n* [[Nathan Paetsch]], former [[NHL]] [[defenceman (ice hockey)|defenceman]]\n* [[William Dutton (speed skater)|William Dutton]], [[2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Olympian]] 500m and 1000m long-track [[speed skater]]\n* [[Jeremy Wotherspoon]], [[speed skater]] with 67 World Cup wins\n* [[Lyndon Rush]], [[2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Olympian]] bronze medal in four-man bobsleigh and [[2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Olympian]] Canadian [[bobsledder]]\n* [[Brianne Theisen-Eaton]], [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012]] and [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Olympian]], [[heptathlete]] and Canadian record-holder in the [[women's pentathlon]], 2016 Olympic bronze medallist (heptathlon)\n* [[Rusty Malinoski]], professional [[wakeboarder]]\n* [[David Schmidtz]], political philosopher\n* [[Dustin Tokarski]], NHL Goaltender\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Humboldt, Saskatchewan}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Humboldt}}\n*{{Official|http://www.humboldt.ca/}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Center=Humboldt\n|North=[[Wakaw, Saskatchewan|Wakaw]]\n|Northeast=[[Annaheim, Saskatchewan|Annaheim]]<br />[[Lake Lenore, Saskatchewan|Lake Lenore]]\n|East=[[Muenster, Saskatchewan|Muenster]]<br />[[St. Gregor, Saskatchewan|St. Gregor]]<br />[[Englefeld, Saskatchewan|Englefeld]]<br />[[Watson, Saskatchewan|Watson]]\n|Southeast=[[Leroy, Saskatchewan|Leroy]]\n|South=[[Burr, Saskatchewan|Burr]]<br />[[Guernsey, Saskatchewan|Guernsey]]<br />[[Lanigan, Saskatchewan|Lanigan]]\n|West=[[Carmel, Saskatchewan|Carmel]]<br />[[Bruno, Saskatchewan|Bruno]]<br />[[Meacham, Saskatchewan|Meacham]]<br />[[Saskatoon]]\n}}\n\n{{Subdivisions of Saskatchewan}}\n\n[[Category:Humboldt, Saskatchewan| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:Division No. 15, Saskatchewan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Humboldt\n|official_name          = City of Humboldt\n|other_name             =\n|settlement_type        = [[List of cities in Saskatchewan|City]]\n|image_skyline          =  Humboldt Sign 012.JPG\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption      