n National Railways (Canadian Northern Railway) Station\n| url =http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=4560&pid=0 \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref> a Post Office (built in 1911\u20131912),<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Post Office\n| url =http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=2880&pid=0 \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref> the Humboldt Provincial Court House (built in 1914\u20131920).<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Provincial Court House\n| url =http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=2871&pid=0| date =  \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref> and the Humboldt Water Tower (built in 1914) has been renovated with a spiral staircase and a circular observation platform on top.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Water Tower\n| url =http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=2787&pid=0| date =  \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref>\n\nThe Humboldt Post Office is a National Historic Site of Canada (built in 1911\u20131912). It houses the [http://www.humboldtmuseum.ca/ Humboldt and District Museum and Gallery].<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Humboldt Post Office National Historic Site of Canada\n| url =http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=11807&pid=0 \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref> Across the street is the Humboldt and District Art Gallery in the old Merchant Bank Building.\n\n[[Marysburg Assumption Church]] is located 16&nbsp;km (10 miles) north of Humboldt.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Marysburg Assumption Church \n| url =http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=8942&pid=0| date =  \n| accessdate =2013-09-18}}</ref>\n[[Mount Carmel Shrine (Saskatchewan)|Mount Carmel Shrine]] is located 23&nbsp;km (14 miles) west and [[St. Peter's Abbey, Saskatchewan|St. Peter's Abbey]] and St. Peter's Cathedral are 10&nbsp;km (6 miles) east of the city in Muenster.\n\nThe Humboldt Murals located in the town centre depict historic scenes.\n\n===Festivals===\n*The Summer Sizzler is held in late-June of each year. The event features a midway, demolition derby, cabaret, slo-pitch tournament, tractor pull, Sizzler Strut Marathon and live on-stage entertainment. On the opening day, there is a parade through downtown and a pancake breakfast at Centennial Park.\n*Canada Day celebrations occur every year on July 1 concluding with fireworks at Water Ridge Park.\n*The Humboldt StreetFest is held in mid-August and is organized by the Humboldt Downtown Business Improvement District.\n\n==Sports and recreation==\n\nHumboldt is home to over 30 acres of parks and open spaces as well as a growing pedestrian trails and pathways system.\nThere are eleven parks around the city, including: A.E. Kilcher Park, Bill Brecht Memorial Park, Carl Schenn Recreational Park, Centennial Park, Civic Park, Glenn Hall Park, Peace Park, St. Augustine School Grounds, St. Dominic School Grounds, Water Ridge Park, St. Elizabeth Park and Wilf Chamney Park.\n\nSituated {{convert|4|mi|km}} west of Humboldt along [[Saskatchewan Highway 5|Highway 5]] and two miles (3&nbsp;km) south is the Kloppenburg Wildlife Refuge. It consists of {{convert|160|acre|km2}} which have never been cultivated.\n\nThe Uniplex is Humboldt's recreational facility featuring a curling rink, an indoor aquatic center, a fitness center and a convention center.  The Elgar Petersen Arena, part of the Uniplex, is a 1,900-seat arena, home to the [[Humboldt Broncos]] of the [[Saskatchewan Junior Hockey League]], two-time [[Royal Bank Cup|National Champions]] and 10-time SJHL Champions, as well as Humboldt's minor hockey teams and club skating club.  Also on the Uniplex grounds is Centennial Park with ball diamonds, a skateboard park and a soccer/football field.\n\nAn 18-hole golf course is located next to Water Ridge Park, which includes walking trails, a spray park and gazebo and the Humboldt Historical Park, mini golf and campground.\n\nSt. Elizabeth Park features Humboldt's 9 hole disc golf course.\n\n==Churches==\nHumboldt has ten churches: Humboldt Alliance Church, St. John's Lutheran, St. Andrew's Anglican Church, St. Augustine Catholic Church, Living Word Ministries, All Saints Ukrainian Catholic Church, Humboldt Bible Church, Westminster United Church of Canada, First Baptist Church and Kingdom Hall of Jehovah's Witnesses.<ref name=\"city\"/>\n\n==Education==\n{{Infobox school\n| name                   = Humboldt Collegiate Institute\n| image                  = \n| image_size             = 250px\n| caption                = \n| motto                  = \n| address                = 509 8th Avenue\n| city                   = Humboldt\n| province               = [[Saskatchewan]]\n| country                = [[Canada]]\n| postalcode             = S0K 2A1\n| coordinates            = \n| opened                 = <!--{{Start date|YYYY}}-->\n| schoolboard            = [[Horizon School Division No. 205]]<br />[[Greater Saskatoon Catholic Schools]]\n| system                 = Public/[[Separate school|Separate]]\n| type                   = Secondary\n| language               = English\n| grades                 = Grade 9 to grade 12\n| principal              = Cory Popoff\n| principal_label2       = Vice principal\n| principal2             = David Millette\n| principal_label3       = Vice principal\n| principal3             = Shaun Gardiner\n| enrollment             = 390<ref name=\"enrollment\">{{Citation|title=Active List of Saskatchewan Schools/Programs|url=http://publications.gov.sk.ca/documents/11/104735-2017-18%20Active%20List%20of%20School%20Division%20Schools.pdf|accessdate=2018-02-10}}</ref>\n| enrollment_as_of       = 2017\n| staff                  = <!-- Count -->\n| team_name              = \n| colours                = \n| website                = [http://hci.hzsd.ca/ Humboldt Collegiate Institute]\n}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                   = Humboldt Public School\n| image                  = \n| image_size             = 250px\n| caption                = \n| motto                  = \n| address                = 509 8th Avenue\n| city                   = Humboldt\n| province               = [[Saskatchewan]]\n| country                = [[Canada]]\n| postalcode             = S0K 2A1\n| coordinates            = \n| opened                 = <!--{{Start date|YYYY}}-->\n| schoolboard            = [[Horizon School Division No. 205]]\n| system                 = Public\n| type                   = Elementary\n| language               = English\n| grades                 = Pre-kindergarten to grade 8\n| principal              = Clayton Parobec\n| principal_label2       = Vice principal\n| principal2             = Darlene Popoff\n| enrollment             = 272<ref name=\"enrollment\"/>\n| enrollment_as_of       = 2017\n| staff                  = <!-- Count -->\n| team_name              = \n| colours                = \n| website                = [http://humboldtpublicschool.hzsd.ca/ Humboldt Public School]\n}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                   = St. Augustine School\n| image                  = \n| image_size             = 250px\n| caption                = \n| motto                  = \n| address                = 1103 8th Avenue\n| city                   = Humboldt\n| province               = [[Saskatchewan]]\n| country                = [[Canada]]\n| postalcode             = S0K 2A1\n| coordinates            = \n| opened                 = {{Start date|1907}}<ref name=\"hauhistory\">{{cite book\n| author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n| title = Celebrating a Century of Faith and Learning - A History of Saskatoon's Catholic Schools\n| year = 2015\n| publisher = Greater Saskatoon Catholic Schools\n| page = 196\n| isbn =978-0-9947443-0-2}}</ref>\n| schoolboard            = [[Greater Saskatoon Catholic Schools]]\n| religion               = [[Catholicism|Catholic]]\n| system                 = [[Separate school|Separate]]\n| type                   = Elementary\n| language               = English\n| grades                 = Kindergarten to grade 8\n| principal              = Cal Theisen\n| principal_label2       = Vice principal\n| principal2             = Cathy Korte-Monz\n| enrollment             = 323<ref name=\"enrollment\" />\n| enrollment_as_of       = 2017\n| staff                  = <!-- Count -->\n| team_name              = \n| colours                = \n| website                = [http://www.gscs.ca/hau St. Augustine School]\n}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                   = St. Dominic School\n| image                  = \n| image_size             = 250px\n| caption                = \n| motto                  = \n| address                = 706 2nd Avenue South\n| city                   = Humboldt\n| province               = [[Saskatchewan]]\n| country                = [[Canada]]\n| postalcode             = S0K 2A1\n| coordinates            = \n| opened                 = {{Start date|1959}}<ref name=\"hdohistory\">{{cite book\n| author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n| title = Celebrating a Century of Faith and Learning - A History of Saskatoon's Catholic Schools\n| year = 2015\n| publisher = Greater Saskatoon Catholic Schools\n| page = 198\n| isbn =978-0-9947443-0-2}}</ref>\n| schoolboard            = [[Greater Saskatoon Catholic Schools]]\n| religion               = [[Catholicism|Catholic]]\n| system                 = [[Separate school|Separate]]\n| type                   = Elementary\n| language               = English\n| grades                 = Kindergarten to grade 8\n| principal              = Chad Knaus\n| principal_label2       = Vice principal\n| principal2             = Celese LeRay-Leicht\n| enrollment             = 221<ref name=\"enrollment\" />\n| enrollment_as_of       = 2017\n| staff                  = <!-- Count -->\n| team_name              = \n| colours                = \n| website                = [http://www.gscs.ca/hdo St. Dominic School]\n}}\nHumboldt has three elementary schools: two Catholic (St. Augustine and St. Dominic) and one public (Humboldt Public School).\n\nIt has one public high school, Humboldt Collegiate Institute. It is co-managed by [[Horizon School Division No. 205]] and [[Greater Saskatoon Catholic Schools]].<ref>{{Citation|title=HCI Joint Operations Committee|url=http://hci.hzsd.ca/01636CEE-011EDEB3?object=/Web%20Pages/JOC&ConfPosition=1&infobar=no|accessdate=2015-06-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304234059/http://hci.hzsd.ca/01636CEE-011EDEB3?object=%2FWeb%20Pages%2FJOC&ConfPosition=1&infobar=no|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The [https://web.archive.org/web/20130704031126/http://hci.hzsd.ca/ Humboldt Collegiate Institute] has senior and junior [[volleyball]] teams (boys' and girls'), senior and junior [[basketball]] teams (boys' and girls'), [[soccer]] (boys' and girls'), [[badminton]], [[golf]], [[Cross country running|cross-country]], [[track & field]] and a nine-man [[Canadian football|football]] program known as HCI Mohawks. The Mohawks won provincial championships in 1975, 1996, 1997, 2008 and 2010.\n\nCarlton Trail Regional College has its headquarters in Humboldt.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\nThe city is served by [[Saskatchewan Highway 5|Highway 5]] and [[Saskatchewan Highway 20|Highway 20]].\n\n[[Humboldt Airport]], (TC LID: CJU4), is located 1 nautical mile (1.9&nbsp;km; 1.2&nbsp;mi) south of the city.\n\nHumboldt is serviced by CN Rail and is home to a number of rail workers.\n\n===Health care===\nHumboldt District Health Complex is home to the Humboldt Hospital and Community Health Services. Humboldt has two medical clinics and four pharmacies in addition to local dental, chiropractic, home care, optometry, physiotherapy as well as health and wellness services.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Saskatoon Health Region (Humboldt District Health Complex)\n| url =https://www.saskatoonhealthregion.ca/locations_services/locations/Pages/Hospitals/Humboldt-District-Health-Complex.aspx\n| accessdate =2014-07-27}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n\n===Humboldt City Council===\nThe Humboldt City Council is the municipal governing body for the city. The council consists of the [[mayor]] and six [[councillor]]s. The current council sits between 2016 and 2020. The last civic election was held on October 26, 2016. Historically, the mayor and councillors were elected to three-year terms; however, the terms have increased to four years. Rob Muench was elected for his first term as Mayor in the 2016 election, he had previously been on City Council for 10 years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.humboldt.ca/files/2012_Humboldt%20Official%20Election%20Results.pdf |title=humboldt.ca |access-date=2014-02-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222175310/http://www.humboldt.ca/files/2012_Humboldt%20Official%20Election%20Results.pdf |archive-date=2014-02-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''2016 Election Results (Councillors)''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n|'''Roger Nordick'''||align=right| '''1,255''' ||align=right| \n|-\n|'''Sandy Weiland''' ||align=right| '''1,233''' ||align=right|  \n|-\n|'''Larry Jorgenson''' ||align=right| '''1,161''' ||align=right| \n|-\n|'''Michael Behiel''' ||align=right| '''1,112''' ||align=right| \n|-\n|'''Lorne Pratchler'''||align=right| '''1,034''' ||align=right| \n|-\n|'''Owen Hopfner'''||align=right| '''914''' ||align=right| \n|-\n|Terry Schatz||align=right| 896 ||align=right| \n|-\n|Amanda Klitch ||align=right| 869 ||align=right| \n|-\n|Justin Arndt||align=right| 637 ||align=right|  \n|-\n|Francis Kunz ||align=right| 443 ||align=right| \n|-\n|Sandor Demeter ||align=right| 146 ||align=right|  \n|-\n\n|}\n\n===Legislative Assembly of Saskatchewan===\n\nThe City of Humboldt is the largest centre in the provincial electoral district of [[Humboldt-Watrous]]. [[Donna Harpauer]] of the [[Saskatchewan Party]] is the current [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]] for the riding.\n\n===Member of Parliament===\n\nThe City of Humboldt is currently within the federal electoral district of [[Carlton Trail\u2014Eagle Creek]] which is represented by [[Kelly Block]] of the [[Conservative Party of Canada]].\n\n== Notable people ==\nNotable people who were born, grew up in or established their fame in Humboldt:\n\n* [[Kelly Bates]], former CFL [[Guard (Canadian football)|guard]], former head coach with the [[Simon Fraser Clan]] (2015-2017), and current assistant coach with the Edmonton Eskimos \n* [[Al Duerr]], former mayor of [[Calgary]], Alberta\n* Andrew Ford, Disney animator and Oscar winner<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bridges|first1=Alicia|title=A puppeteer of pixels: Sask. animator works on Disney blockbusters|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/saskatchewan-animator-andrew-ford-disney-1.3936095|accessdate=10 May 2017|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Jillian Gallays]], wrestler\n* [[Glenn Hall]], former professional [[ice hockey]] [[goaltender]]. [[Stanley Cup]] champion and [[Hockey Hall of Fame]] inductee\n* [[Lylian Klimek]], sculptor\n* [[Ross Lonsberry]], professional [[ice hockey]] player, two-time Stanley Cup champion with the [[Philadelphia Flyers]]\n* [[Otto Lang]], Rhodes Scholar, law school dean, Federal Cabinet Minister, and executive\n* [[Brad Lauer]], former [[NHL]] [[forward (ice hockey)|forward]] and current assistant coach with the [[Anaheim Ducks]]\n* [[Kyle McLaren]], former [[NHL]]  [[defenceman (ice hockey)|defenceman]]\n* [[Brendan Witt]], former [[NHL]] [[defenceman (ice hockey)|defenceman]]\n* [[Nathan Paetsch]], former [[NHL]] [[defenceman (ice hockey)|defenceman]]\n* [[William Dutton (speed skater)|William Dutton]], [[2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Olympian]] 500m and 1000m long-track [[speed skater]]\n* [[Jeremy Wotherspoon]], [[speed skater]] with 67 World Cup wins\n* [[Lyndon Rush]], [[2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Olympian]] bronze medal in four-man bobsleigh and [[2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Olympian]] Canadian [[bobsledder]]\n* [[Brianne Theisen-Eaton]], [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012]] and [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Olympian]], [[heptathlete]] and Canadian record-holder in the [[women's pentathlon]], 2016 Olympic bronze medallist (heptathlon)\n* [[Rusty Malinoski]], professional [[wakeboarder]]\n* [[David Schmidtz]], political philosopher\n* [[Dustin Tokarski]], NHL Goaltender\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Humboldt, Saskatchewan}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Humboldt}}\n*{{Official|http://www.humboldt.ca/}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Center=Humboldt\n|North=[[Wakaw, Saskatchewan|Wakaw]]\n|Northeast=[[Annaheim, Saskatchewan|Annaheim]]<br />[[Lake Lenore, Saskatchewan|Lake Lenore]]\n|East=[[Muenster, Saskatchewan|Muenster]]<br />[[St. Gregor, Saskatchewan|St. Gregor]]<br />[[Englefeld, Saskatchewan|Englefeld]]<br />[[Watson, Saskatchewan|Watson]]\n|Southeast=[[Leroy, Saskatchewan|Leroy]]\n|South=[[Burr, Saskatchewan|Burr]]<br />[[Guernsey, Saskatchewan|Guernsey]]<br />[[Lanigan, Saskatchewan|Lanigan]]\n|West=[[Carmel, Saskatchewan|Carmel]]<br />[[Bruno, Saskatchewan|Bruno]]<br />[[Meacham, Saskatchewan|Meacham]]<br />[[Saskatoon]]\n}}\n\n{{Subdivisions of Saskatchewan}}\n\n[[Category:Humboldt, Saskatchewan| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:Division No. 15, Saskatchewan]]\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "tidy wikitable options", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Humboldt,_Saskatchewan"}
{"title_page": "Songs from the Big Chair", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Songs from the Big Chair\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Tears for Fears]]\n| cover      = Tears for Fears Songs from the Big Chair.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 25 February 1985\n| recorded   = 1984{{efn|\"Broken\" (live) recorded December 1983 at [[Hammersmith Odeon]]}}\n| studio     = [[The Wool Hall]] ([[Beckington]], England)\n| genre      =\n* [[New wave music|New wave]]<ref name=\"50bestPM\">{{cite web|last1=Jackson|first1=Josh|title=The 50 Best New Wave Albums|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/09/the-best-new-wave-albums.html?p=2|website=[[Paste magazine]]}}</ref>\n* [[progressive pop]]<ref name=\"munro\">{{cite web|last1=Munro|first1=Scott|title=Steven Wilson meets Bollywood in Permanating video|url=http://teamrock.com/news/2017-07-21/steven-wilson-meets-bollywood-in-permanating-video|website=[[Team Rock]]|date=July 21, 2017}}</ref>\n| length     = 41:52\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Phonogram Inc.|Phonogram]]|[[Mercury Records|Mercury]]}}\n| producer   = [[Chris Hughes (musician)|Chris Hughes]]\n| prev_title = [[The Hurting]]\n| prev_year  = 1983\n| next_title = [[The Seeds of Love]]\n| next_year  = 1989\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Songs from the Big Chair\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Mothers Talk]]\n | single1date = 6 August 1984\n | single2     = [[Shout (Tears for Fears song)|Shout]]\n | single2date = 19 November 1984\n | single3     = [[Everybody Wants to Rule the World]]\n | single3date = 18 March 1985\n | single4     = [[Head over Heels (Tears for Fears song)|Head over Heels]]\n | single4date = 10 June 1985\n | single5     = [[I Believe (Tears for Fears song)|I Believe (A Soulful Re-Recording)]]\n | single5date = 30 September 1985\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Songs from the Big Chair''''' is the second [[Album#Studio|studio album]] by English [[pop rock]] band [[Tears for Fears]], released on 25 February 1985 by [[Phonogram Records]]. The album peaked at number two in the UK and at number one in the US and Canada, becoming a multi-platinum seller in all three countries. It also reached number one in Germany and the Netherlands and Top 10 positions in various other countries including Australia, Switzerland, New Zealand and Italy. It spawned the international hit singles \"[[Mothers Talk]]\", \"[[Shout (Tears for Fears song)|Shout]]\", \"[[Everybody Wants to Rule the World]]\", \"[[Head over Heels (Tears for Fears song)|Head over Heels]]\", and \"[[I Believe (Tears for Fears song)|I Believe]]\". It remains their best-selling album to date.\n\nA companion video documentary entitled ''[[Scenes from the Big Chair]]'' was released in late 1985. Once the band had finished a lengthy touring and promotion schedule for the album, they took an extended hiatus from the music industry.\n\n== Background ==\n{{Quote box\n| quote=\"The title was my idea. It's a bit perverse but then you've got to understand our sense of humour. The 'Big Chair' idea is from this brilliant film called ''Sybil'' about a girl with 16 different personalities. She'd been tortured incredibly by her mother as a child and the only place she felt safe, the only time she could really be herself was when she was sitting in her analyst's chair. She felt safe, comfortable and wasn't using her different faces as a defence. It's kind of an 'up yours' to the English music press who really fucked us up for a while. This is ''us'' now \u2013 and they can't get at us anymore.\"\n| source = \u2014[[Curt Smith]] explains the album's title, March 1985<ref>{{cite journal |first=Helen |last=FitzGerald |title=On the Beach |periodical=[[Melody Maker]] |publisher=[[IPC Media]] |location=London, England |pages=20\u201321 & 29 |date=9 March 1985}}</ref>\n| width  = 20%\n| align  = left\n| style  = padding:10px;\n}}\n\nOriginally, the album was to be titled ''The Working Hour'', but Roland Orzabal fought to change it to ''Songs from the Big Chair'',<ref name=\"classic\">{{cite episode |title=Tears For Fears - Songs From The Big Chair |series=Classic Albums |date=14 February 2020 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000f8xc |network=BBC Four}}</ref> which was derived from the 1976 television film ''[[Sybil (1976 film)|Sybil]]'' about a woman with [[multiple personality disorder]] who only feels safe when she is sitting in her analyst's \"big chair\". A mostly-instrumental track called \"The Big Chair\" (which includes dialogue samples from the film) was released as the B-side of \"Shout\" in 1984, but was not included on the album.\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/songs-from-the-big-chair-mw0000038029 |title=Songs from the Big Chair \u2013 Tears for Fears |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=23 October 2009 |last=Swihart |first=Stanton}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2score = A+<ref name=\"cos\">{{cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/11/album-review-tears-for-fears-songs-from-the-big-chair-reissue/ |title=Tears for Fears \u2013 Songs from the Big Chair [Reissue] |work=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=11 November 2014 |accessdate=23 May 2015 |last=Roffman |first=Michael}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev3score  = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book |title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music |last=Larkin |first=Colin |authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer) |publisher=[[Omnibus Press]] |edition=5th concise |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-85712-595-8|title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music }}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/dec/11/tears-for-fears-songs-from-the-big-chair-box-set-review |title=Tears for Fears: Songs from the Big Chair box set review \u2013 beefy, bizarre preposterous pop |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |date=11 December 2014 |accessdate=23 May 2015 |last=Gibsone |first=Harriet}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Tears for Fears: Songs from the Big Chair |journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]] |location=London |issue= |date= |page=115 |quote='Everybody Wants to Rule the World'{{'}}s lens flare and Robert Wyatt homage 'I Believe' prove durable.}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6score = 8.9/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/tears-for-fears-songs-from-the-big-chair/ |title=Tears for Fears: Songs from the Big Chair |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=20 August 2017 |accessdate=20 August 2017 |last=Rosenberg |first=Tal}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev7score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"qreview\">{{cite journal |title=Tears for Fears: Songs from the Big Chair |journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |location=London |issue= |date= |page=115}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Record Collector]]''\n| rev8score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Elliott\">{{cite journal |url=http://recordcollectormag.com/reviews/songs-big-chair |title=Tears For Fears \u2013 Songs From The Big Chair |journal=[[Record Collector]] |location=London |issue=435 |date=December 2014 |accessdate=17 November 2015 |last=Elliott |first=Mark}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Smash Hits]]''\n| rev9Score = 8/10<ref name=\"Cranna\">{{cite journal |title=Tears for Fears: Songs from the Big Chair (Mercury) |journal=[[Smash Hits]] |location=London |volume=7 |issue=5 |date=28 February \u2013 13 March 1985 |last=Cranna |first=Ian |page=21}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10score = B<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv5-85.php |title=Christgau's Consumer Guide |work=[[The Village Voice]] |location=New York |date=28 May 1985 |accessdate=9 January 2012 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref>\n}}\n\nIn his review of ''Songs from the Big Chair'', critic Barry McIlheney of ''[[Melody Maker]]'' stated that \"none of you should really be too surprised that Tears for Fears have made such an ''excellent'' album\", calling it \"an album that fully justifies the rather sneering, told-you-so looks adopted by Curt Smith and Roland Orzabal on the sleeve\", before concluding, \"An awful lot of people will, of course, go on and on about overcoats, [[The Lotus Eaters (band)|The Lotus Eaters]] and an alleged lack of depth. And an awful lot of people will have to eat an awful lot of words.\"<ref name=\"MM19850302\">{{cite journal |title=Tears for Fears: Songs from the Big Chair |journal=[[Melody Maker]] |location=London |date=2 March 1985 |last=McIlheney |first=Barry |page=23}}</ref> Ian Cranna of ''[[Smash Hits]]'' described it as \"looser, more exploratory than before\" in nature, and noted its \"unflinching lyrical honesty\".<ref name=\"Cranna\" /> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' critic Don Shewey wrote that Tears for Fears \"sounds a lot like a lot of other British bands\" and observed traces of \"[[U2]]'s social conscience, [[Echo and the Bunnymen|the Bunnymen]]'s echoing guitars and [[XTC]]'s contorted pop wit\" on the album, but commented that Chris Hughes' production \"nudges ''Songs from the Big Chair'' slightly ahead of the pack.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/tearsforfears/albums/album/104567/review/6067723/songs_from_the_big_chair |title=Tears for Fears: Songs From the Big Chair |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York |issue=448 |date=23 May 1985 |accessdate=23 October 2009 |last=Shewey |first=Don |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121200739/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/tearsforfears/albums/album/104567/review/6067723/songs_from_the_big_chair |archivedate=21 November 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] was less enthusiastic in his review for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', observing some substantial lyrics, particularly on \"The Working Hour\", and musical elements such as an \"uncommon command of guitar and piano, [[Baker Street (song)|Baker Street]] sax, synthesizers more jagged than is deemed mete by the arbiters of dance-pop accessibility\". However, he felt these are all beneath grandiloquent lamentations suggesting \"a depth and drama English lads have been falling short on since the dawn of progressive rock.\"<ref name=\"Christgau\" />\n\nIn a retrospective review published on [[AllMusic]], Stanton Swihart wrote: \"In the loping, percolating 'Everybody Wants to Rule the World', Tears for Fears perfectly captured the zeitgeist of the mid-'80s while impossibly managing to also create a dreamy, timeless pop classic. ''Songs from the Big Chair'' is one of the finest statements of the decade.\"<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> Mark Elliott of ''[[Record Collector]]'' agreed, while adding that it contained the band's \"most consistently interesting material\".<ref name=\"Elliott\" /> ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' remarked that the album \"zeroed in on every angsty adolescent's desire to feel heroic, with a sound of spotlit, spacious sophistication plus anthemic choruses you'd bet your house on.\"<ref name=\"qreview\" /> In ''[[Stylus Magazine]]'', Andrew Unterberger concluded that \"even today, when all rock musicians seem to be able to do is be emotional and honest, the brutality and power of ''Songs from the Big Chair''{{'}}s catharsis is still quite shocking.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/on_second_thought/tears-for-fears-songs-from-the-big-chair.htm |title=Tears for Fears \u2013 Songs from the Big Chair \u2013 On Second Thought |work=[[Stylus Magazine]] |date=28 February 2006 |accessdate=23 May 2015 |last=Unterberger |first=Andrew}}</ref> ''Songs from the Big Chair'' has been included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book |title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition |editor1-last=Dimery |editor1-first=Robert |publisher=[[Universe Publishing|Universe]] |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-7893-2074-2}}</ref> ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' listed the album at number 95 on its list of the best albums of the 1980s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/feature/best-albums-of-the-1980s/308 |title=The 100 Best Albums of the 1980s |work=[[Slant Magazine]] |date=5 March 2012 |accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the album was the focus of an episode of the BBC's ''[[Classic Albums]]'' documentary series. The episode included new interviews with key personnel including Orzabal, Smith, Ian Stanley, producer Chris Hughes, engineer Dave Bascombe, and [[Artists and repertoire|A&R man]] David Bates. Additional interviewees included [[Oleta Adams]] and [[John Grant (musician)|John Grant]].<ref name=\"classic\"/>\n\n== Re-issues ==\nIn 1998, [[Mobile Fidelity Sound Lab|MFSL]] remastered and re-issued the album with an extended \"Head over Heels\" (running 5:24) and two bonus tracks (extended mixes of \"Shout\" and \"Everybody Wants to Rule the World\").\n\nThe album was [[remaster]]ed and re-issued on CD in 1999 with bonus tracks, including B-sides and remixes. The track listing is based on the Special Edition cassette version of the album, which featured five B-sides as bonus tracks\u2014including three tracks (\"The Conflict\", \"The Marauders\" and \"Broken Revisited\") from ''[[The Hurting]]'' period. In addition to these tracks, it includes two remixes.\n\nThe album was re-released again in a deluxe edition 2-disc format in 2006 with the full collection of B-sides and many alternate versions and remixes of the album's tracks.\n\nIn 2014, the album was released by Universal Music Japan on SHM-SACD.\n\nTo mark the album's 30th anniversary, Universal Music released the album in five different formats on 10 November 2014, including a 6-disc Super Deluxe Edition which includes four CDs and two DVDs (1 audio, 1 video).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pryor|first1=Terrance|title=Tears For Fears To Reissue 'Songs From The Big Chair'|url=http://www.prefixmag.com/news/tears-for-fears-to-reissue-songs-from-the-big-chai/78335/|website=prefixmag.com|publisher=Prefix Magazine|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref> This edition also includes a 30-page replica 1985 tour programme and a 32-page booklet. Additional formats released simultaneously include another 2-disc Deluxe Edition, a single disc remastered edition, a 180-gram heavyweight vinyl album, and a \"Pure Audio\" [[Blu-ray]] edition. The 5.1 surround sound mix is done by renowned remixer and progressive rock musician [[Steven Wilson]]. The 6-disc set was reissued in 2020, to commemorate the album's 35th anniversary, along with a new vinyl [[picture disc]] of the album.\n\n== Track listing ==\n=== Original release ===\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side one\n| extra_column = Writer(s)\n| title1  = [[Shout (Tears for Fears song)|Shout]]\n| extra1  = [[Roland Orzabal]], [[Ian Stanley]]\n| length1 = 6:32\n| title2  = The Working Hour\n| extra2  = Orzabal, Stanley, [[Manny Elias]]\n| length2 = 6:30\n| title3  = [[Everybody Wants to Rule the World]]\n| extra3  = Orzabal, Stanley, [[Chris Hughes (record producer)|Chris Hughes]]\n| length3 = 4:10\n| title4  = [[Mothers Talk]]\n| extra4  = Orzabal, Stanley\n| length4 = 5:09\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| extra_column = Writer(s)\n| title1  = [[I Believe (Tears for Fears song)|I Believe]]\n| extra1  = Orzabal\n| length1 = 4:53\n| title2  = Broken\n| extra2  = Orzabal\n| length2 = 2:38\n| title3  = [[Head over Heels (Tears for Fears song)|Head over Heels]]/Broken (Live)\n| extra3  = Orzabal, [[Curt Smith]]\n| length3 = 5:01\n| title4  = Listen\n| extra4  = Stanley, Orzabal\n| length4 = 6:48\n}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n*\"I Believe\" is dedicated to '[[Robert Wyatt]] (if he's listening)'<ref name =\"VinylPower\">''Songs from the Big Chair'' vinyl record (1985)</ref>\n*In some US editions, the live reprise of \"Broken\" was omitted, and the end of \"Head over Heels\" led directly into \"Listen\". On these same US editions, the full 5:09 version of \"Mothers Talk\" was replaced with the 3:53 short version, resulting in an overall runtime two minutes and ten seconds shorter than the original album.\n*In some later Canadian editions, \"Head over Heels\" and the live reprise of \"Broken\" was split into two separate tracks creating a nine-track release; the booklet and other CD artwork still had the original tracklist, however.\n*A limited edition UK cassette version of the album contained many bonus tracks (\"The Big Chair\", \"Empire Building\", \"The Marauders\", \"Broken Revisited\", \"The Conflict\") as well as a short version of \"The Working Hour\" (titled \"Piano Version\", although there is none); the configuration was recreated on CD for the 30th anniversary with even more additional tracks appended.\n\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = 1999 remastered CD bonus tracks\n| extra_column = Writer(s)\n| title9  = The Big Chair\n| extra9  = Orzabal, Smith, Stanley, Hughes\n| length9 = 3:21\n| title10  = Empire Building\n| extra10  = Smith, Orzabal, Stanley\n|length10 = 2:52\n| title11  = The Marauders\n| extra11  = Orzabal, Stanley\n| length11 = 4:16\n| title12  = Broken Revisited\n| extra12  = Orzabal\n| length12 = 5:16\n| title13  = The Conflict\n| extra13  = Orzabal, Smith, Stanley\n| length13 = 4:05\n| title14  = Mothers Talk\n| note14   = [[United States|U.S.]] remix\n| length14 = 4:13\n| title15  = Shout\n| note15   = U.S. remix\n| length15 = 8:02\n}}\n\n'''Note'''\n*\"Mothers Talk\" (U.S. remix) on the remastered CD is the correct version of this remix, but has had additional reverb applied. The 1999 remaster is the only CD on which this \"extra reverb\" version can be found.\n\n=== Deluxe Edition (2006) ===\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = Disc one\n| extra_column    = Writer(s)\n| title1          